<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Would Seek Clinton's Advice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- At the very moment he is trying to emerge from President
Clinton's shadow, Vice President Al Gore said Sunday he would not hesitate to
seek Clinton's counsel if he succeeds him. ''Why would I rule that out?'' Gore
said in an interview with The Associated Press. The vice president, battling
Republican attempts to shackle him to Clinton's personal scandals, also said he
would serve his own term in the Oval Office ''according to the highest values.''
Gore spoke on the eve of Clinton's valedictory Monday night to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Northeast Storm Causes Flash Floods
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) -- Residents of two northern New Jersey towns were
evacuated Sunday and others were put on alert in the wake of torrential
downpours that washed out bridges and roads, broke through a dam and prompted
fears of mudslides. Officials estimated that Saturday's downpour, which dumped
more than 14 inches of rain on the area around Sparta, caused hundreds of
million of dollars in damage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas Reopen Border Liaisons
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, South Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea reopened border liaison
offices Monday, four years after they were closed because of political tensions.
Relations between the two Koreas have warmed significantly since their leaders
held a historic summit in Pyongyang, the North's capital, in June. In follow-up
talks by their deputies in Seoul two weeks ago, the Koreas agreed to reopen the
border liaison offices. The liaison offices first opened in 1992 to work as
government channels of dialogue. They closed four years later after a dispute
over a North Korean submarine that washed ashore in South Korea.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Paraguay VP Vote Too Close To Call
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguay's vote for a successor to its slain vice
president appeared extremely close Sunday, with early returns giving the
opposition candidate a slim lead over the late politician's son. The special,
one-office election is seen by the opposition as a chance to diminish the power
of the Colorado Party, which has ruled this South American country for 53 years.
The post of vice president has been empty since Luis Argana was gunned down in
the street in March 1999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford: Tires Made During Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Many of the 6.5 million Firestone tires being
recalled were made during a strike at the company's Decatur, Ill., plant, Ford
Motor Co. said Sunday. The tires are under investigation in hundreds of crashes
that caused at least 46 deaths. Ford conducted an analysis of its Firestone
tires and the complaints it had received to pin down where the tires were made.
The number of complaints was 10 times higher for the 15-inch ATX tires made in
Decatur than for the Wilderness tires, said Jason Vines, Ford's vice president
of communications. At the time, union workers at the plant were on strike, and
the plant was operating with replacement workers and managers.
Bridgestone/Firestone said the strike had nothing to do with the problems.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cloning Pioneers End Pig Research
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The creators of Dolly the Sheep are halting their research
into genetically modifying pigs for human organ transplants, one of the
scientists said Sunday. The decision is motivated in part by fears that
transplanting animal organs into people could unleash deadly new viruses among
the human population. California-based Geron Bio-Med, which owns exclusive
rights to biotechnology developed by Edinburgh's Roslin Institute -- where Dolly
was created -- has decided to cut funding for the work, said Ian Wilmut, leader
of the team that created Dolly, the first clone made from an adult animal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
LinuxWorld Conference To Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- As the new kid on the block, the Linux computer
operating system once had few friends besides the stereotypical technology geek
whose idea of fun was spending hours rewriting software code. But as that same
kid begins to gather dozens of new electronic toys around it, Linux has suddenly
become part of the in crowd -- and an increasing threat to Microsoft Corp.'s
Windows monopoly. As the third annual LinuxWorld Conference &AMP; Expo opens this
week here, companies such as Hewlett-Packard are joining Dell Computer and IBM
Corp. in designating Linux a ''strategic'' operating system as each works to
gain market share in the high-end server computer market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Beat Angels 4-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Roger Clemens pitched four-hit ball for 6 2-3 innings
Sunday night, winning his sixth straight decision as the New York Yankees beat
the Anaheim Angels 4-1. The Yankees managed two runs off rookie right-hander
Ramon Ortiz on a bases-loaded walk and a balk to salvage the finale of the
three-game series. New York leads Boston by four games in the AL East, while
Anaheim is two games behind Oakland and Cleveland in the wild-card race.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
