<HEADLINE> Tammy Faye Plugs New Documentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK HILL, S.C. (AP) -- This documentary is a must-see, at least
in the eyes of Tammy Faye Bakker-Messner.
</P>
<P>
   The former wife of fallen televanglist Jim Bakker said the new
documentary, ''The Eyes of Tammy Faye,'' which shows the highs and
lows of her public life, treats her right.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very fair portrayal,'' she told Friday's edition of The
Herald of Rock Hill from her home in Matthews, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little irreverent at times,'' but that's OK, she said.
''That's been my life. I've had black places and wonderful light
places.''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-minute film delves into the rise and fall of Tammy Faye
and Jim Bakker's Praise The Lord ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Of the good reviews she's hearing, Bakker-Messner said, ''I'm
the most shocked of anybody. I thought after 12 years, people would
be sick of this story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
