<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dallas Searches For Superintendent  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN PARROTT
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- If finding a long-term superintendent were a test,
Dallas school trustees would have earned an F.
</P>
<P>
   After firing Bill Rojas last month, they've launched their third
search in four years for a leader who can manage the 10th largest
school district in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a process all too familiar to an urban district that has
gained a national reputation for instability. And it has many
wondering if the district's poor track record will repel the most
qualified candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, a brash-talking New York native who had been
superintendent in San Francisco, sparred with the school board for
most of his 11-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
   He was fired 7-1 by trustees who invoked a ''good rapport''
clause in his contract. ''He was lacking in some diplomacy,'' said
trustee Jose Plata. ''You can't be a South Bronx, New York, guy in
Dallas all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was hired last August to replace Yvonne Gonzalez, who was
sentenced to federal prison for embezzling $16,000 in district
funds to buy personal furniture.
</P>
<P>
   When trustees hired Rojas -- a surprise candidate -- they lauded
his experience working with minority students in San Francisco.
Trustees agreed to pay him a base salary of $260,000, the highest
in the nation at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But even a hefty salary may not be enough to lure top applicants
to replace Rojas, said Fred Bateman, executive director of the
Urban Superintendents Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dallas is sort of red-flagged in everybody's eyes as one of
those unstable places,'' he said. ''People say to themselves, 'Why
should I -- even for that amount of money -- throw myself into the
fiery furnace?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is not the only school district with a revolving door.
Since May 1999, 14 of the nation's 25 largest school districts have
replaced their superintendents or began searching for a new leader.
In at least eight of those cases, the deposed superintendents had
difficulty getting along with school board members or other elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman noted that superintendents of urban districts stay put
an average of 2.3 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a harder job these days,'' he said. ''You must be as much
a politician as an educator and a manager. It's kind of a
superhuman kind of person.''
</P>
<P>
   While trustees cited Rojas' poor communication and abrasive
style in firing him, he called his termination ''vindictive
behavior by a group of micromanagers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who had offered his resignation before he was fired July
5, has appealed the school board's decision to pay him $90,000 in
severance, instead of buying out his contract for $520,000. The
school district last week sued Rojas, arguing that he is not
entitled to any additional pay.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas must next hire someone who can work harmoniously with the
board and public, said Houston school board trustee Donald McAdams,
author of the book, ''Fighting to Save Our Urban Schools And
Winning: Lessons from Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   A search committee of three trustees and four community and
business leaders is compiling a ''short list'' of five candidates
for the full school board to consider later this month. The group
will consider non-educators as well as professionals in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to coming up with a new, absolutely
bulletproof superintendent,'' said Ken Zornes, a trustee who is
leading the search committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk, whose two daughters attend public
schools, said it will take more than a new superintendent to
stabilize the district. He has called for the resignation of the
board of trustees, who he said have failed to lead the district.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no confidence that the people who picked the last three
superintendents will be successful,'' Kirk said. ''The definition
of insanity is doing the same thing over and over again but
expecting to get different results.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas residents attending a recent public forum told the search
committee they want a proven leader who embraces the community and
its 163,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know as well as I know, with all the changes at the top,
that we've had too many superintendents in too short a time,'' said
businessman Terry Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Urban Superintendents Association of America:
http://www.usaa.org
</P>
<P>
   National Center for Education Statistics: http://nces.ed.gov
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Independent School District: http://www.dallasisd.org
</P>
</TEXT>
