<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman To Attend Producer's Party  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- On his first evening at the
Democratic convention, vice presidential hopeful Joseph Lieberman
will hobnob at a Hollywood producer's home with executives whose
companies paid $5,000 to $25,000 for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   The host, producer David Salzman, hails from an industry that
Lieberman has criticized for fomenting violence and sex, and
produced a daytime talk show the Connecticut senator once
criticized.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that helped underwrite the reception include
Microsoft Corp., the software giant that is battling the Clinton
administration over antitrust violations, and Koch Industries, the
oil pipeline under investigation by the Clinton Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor is the New Democrat Network, a political action
committee that Lieberman helped found in 1996 to advance the ideas
of centrist, pro-business Democrats like himself.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC has collected tens of thousands of dollars in donations
from oil, tobacco and drug companies criticized by his new running
mate, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   What message does it send?
</P>
<P>
   ''These are some real mixed messages we're getting,'' lamented
Larry Makinson, head of the Center for Responsive Politics that
studies campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of the groups Gore has been attacking, he seems to be
taking money from, and the ones Gore is popular with, like
Hollywood, Lieberman is attacking,'' Makinson said. ''They've got
both their money bases covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Rosenberg, president of the New Democrat Network, said the
event Tuesday night was planned for months, long before Lieberman
was named Gore's running mate, to give pro-business Democrats a
chance to mingle with corporate supporters.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore picked Lieberman as running mate, the event was
changed to a tribute to the Connecticut senator.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always coming and now this is going to turn into a
celebration of our founder. People really like Joe and are
passionate about him as a leader of the new Democratic movement,''
Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was one of four events for companies or individuals
who donated $10,000 or $25,000 to help underwrite the PAC's
activities at the Democratic convention. The executives also have
access to a luxury skybox in the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Microsoft and Koch, contributors also included America
Online, AT&AMP;T Wireless, Lucent Technologies and Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg said about half the 200 executives invited to
Tuesday's reception have never donated to NDN. They'll get the
chance to mingle with the likes of Lieberman, Sens. Bob Graham of
Florida and John Breaux and Mary Landrieu of Louisiana and Reps.
Cal Dooley, D-Calif., Adam Smith, D-Wash., and Jim Moran, D-Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an opportunity to reach out to some of the people
we've gotten to know in L.A., get them some exposure to the NDN and
new Democrats. We hope some of them will become supporters,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the reception was moved from a restaurant to
Salzman's home in Beverly Hills. ''We thought it would be a better
place to have a party,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman is a prominent Democratic supporter and well-known
Hollywood figure whose works range from Oscar awards shows and the
1993 Clinton inauguration to TV shows like ''Dallas,'' ''Full
House,'' ''Mad TV'' and ''Fresh Prince of Bel Air.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also listed as executive producer of the Jenny Jones talk
show that one of his companies produced -- one of those singled out
for criticism by Lieberman. Salzman's home phone number is unlisted
and he could not be reached for comment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg said he doesn't think the event at Salzman's home
sends a double message.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator Lieberman has been concerned about some of the
messages sent by the entertainment industry. But that industry also
produces plenty of great stuff too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In talk show appearances Sunday, Lieberman said he would use the
convention to renew his call for less violence and sex in public
entertainment. ''I will, and I think that's exactly the message
that the vice president has,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find that the average family feels as if it's in a
competition with a lot of the stuff ... coming out of the
entertainment industry. And government has to be on the side of
standing with those people to help them, because they feel helpless
against the big entertainment industry,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   NDN touts itself as a ''political venture capital fund'' which
endorses and contributes to pro-business Democrats who want to
''lead the U.S. and the world into the 21st century and the
Internet Age.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission records show it has given more than
$200,000 to support pro-business candidates this election cycle. It
has raised more than $400,000 in donations in 2000 alone.
</P>
<P>
   Among the donors who have given money to the group: oil giants
Texaco, Koch and Occidental, pharmaceutical companies Merck,
Pfizer, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Glaxo Wellcome, and tobacco
company Brown and Williamson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
