<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Would Seek Clinton's Advice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- At the very moment he is trying to emerge from President
Clinton's shadow, Vice President Al Gore said Sunday he would not hesitate to
seek Clinton's counsel if he succeeds him. ''Why would I rule that out?'' Gore
said in an interview with The Associated Press. The vice president, battling
Republican attempts to shackle him to Clinton's personal scandals, also said he
would serve his own term in the Oval Office ''according to the highest values.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arafat Arrives in Beijing For Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat visited China on Monday to
brief Chinese leaders on the failed Middle East peace summit and his plans to
declare an independent Palestinian state on Sept. 13. A Chinese vice foreign
minister, Ji Peiding, and a crowd of Arab ambassadors greeted Arafat on his
arrival early Monday at Beijing's airport. During his one-day visit, Arafat was
to meet President Jiang Zemin to convey his impression of last month's summit
and to discuss a possible unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state next
month, said Moustapha Saphariny, the Palestinian ambassador in Beijing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Northeast Storm Causes Flash Floods
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) -- Residents of two northern New Jersey towns were
evacuated Sunday and others were put on alert in the wake of torrential
downpours that washed out bridges and roads, broke through a dam and prompted
fears of mudslides. Officials estimated that Saturday's downpour, which dumped
more than 14 inches of rain on the area around Sparta, caused hundreds of
million of dollars in damage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas Reopen Border Liaisons
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, South Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea reopened border liaison
offices Monday, four years after they were closed because of political tensions.
Relations between the two Koreas have warmed significantly since their leaders
held a historic summit in Pyongyang, the North's capital, in June. In follow-up
talks by their deputies in Seoul two weeks ago, the Koreas agreed to reopen the
border liaison offices. The liaison offices first opened in 1992 to work as
government channels of dialogue. They closed four years later after a dispute
over a North Korean submarine that washed ashore in South Korea.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanan Fights Intolerant Image
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Reform Party presidential contender Pat Buchanan
sought a more tolerant image Sunday in his effort to strengthen his long-shot
White House bid against both legal and political challenges. At a news
conference later, Buchanan complimented Joseph Lieberman, the Connecticut
senator and Orthodox Jew selected as running mate by Democrat Al Gore.
Buchanan's opponents, who say John Hagelin is the real Reform Party nominee and
should receive $12.5 million in federal funds, say Buchanan's comments of
tolerance are a political makeover that can't mask the fact that some white
supremacist groups support him.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon Strike Enters Second Week
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Verizon Communications and its unions remain at odds over
a new contract proposal on the table, dashing hopes that thousands of telephone
technicians and operators would soon leave the picket lines and return to work.
The company, seeking to resolve a strike that has dragged on since Aug. 6,
offered the unions what it called a ''revised comprehensive offer'' early
Sunday. But union negotiators quickly denounced the offer, saying it failed to
address such key issues as mandatory overtime and the shifting of workloads to
areas of cheaper labor. On some points, the proposal represents a step backward,
union officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
LinuxWorld Conference To Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- As the new kid on the block, the Linux computer
operating system once had few friends besides the stereotypical technology geek
whose idea of fun was spending hours rewriting software code. But as that same
kid begins to gather dozens of new electronic toys around it, Linux has suddenly
become part of the in crowd -- and an increasing threat to Microsoft Corp.'s
Windows monopoly. As the third annual LinuxWorld Conference &AMP; Expo opens this
week here, companies such as Hewlett-Packard are joining Dell Computer and IBM
Corp. in designating Linux a ''strategic'' operating system as each works to
gain market share in the high-end server computer market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Beat Rangers 4-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek hit two-run
singles in the third inning and the Boston Red Sox beat the Texas Rangers 4-2
Sunday night. Gabe Kapler extended the major leagues' longest hitting streak
this season to 26 games with a sixth-inning single, but Texas had just five
hits. The Rangers have been held to seven hits or less in four straight games.
Tomo Ohka (1-2) pitched 5 2-3 innings, his longest stint in 12 major league
appearances the past two seasons for Boston. Derek Lowe pitched the ninth for
his 26th save in 31 opportunities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
