<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrities and Politicians Mix  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The cast of Showtime's ''Resurrection Blvd.''
did more than just help get out the vote at the Latino Committee
2000 gathering Sunday at Paramount Pictures studios.
</P>
<P>
   They also got out the word on their critically acclaimed but
struggling TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to get the message out to the community to watch
'Resurrection Blvd.,' to subscribe to Showtime,'' said actor Tony
Plano, who plays Roberto Santiago, the patriarch of a Hispanic
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''We as Hispanics are 11 percent of the population, but we're
only 2 to 3 percent of the TV population. We need this show,''
Plano said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Resurrection Blvd.,'' with one of the first all-Latino casts
on television, follows a family of boxers living in East Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Mauricio Mendoza and Ruth Livier, who play siblings on
the show, couldn't decide how the fictional Santiago family would
react to the convention hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd all be worrying about boxing,'' Mendoza said. But his
fictional sibling disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be the young generation -- my character and
Mauricio's character -- who would be rallying the family to get
involved,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The actors signed autographs and posed for pictures with
star-struck delegates, many of whom admitted they didn't have
Showtime on their TVs.
</P>
<P>
   But actor Esai Morales, also known for his roles opposite Lou
Diamond Phillips in ''La Bamba'' and Jimmy Smits in ''My Family,''
encouraged one Florida delegate to get cable.
</P>
<P>
   ''You need to watch this,'' Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motown's legendary founder Berry Gordy put it simply: ''It's
like old home week.''
</P>
<P>
   From the red carpets laid out at the California Science Center
to the dirty cement sidewalks outside The Conga Room, the parade of
celebrities and politicians was nearly nonstop across town
Saturday, two days before the start of the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Harry Belafonte chatted with Rep. Maxine Waters,
D-Calif., at the African-American Committee 2000 and Beyond gala at
the Science Center. On the other side of the room, Gordy embraced
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Some 450 people were tempted by soul food ranging from potato
pie to fried okra.
</P>
<P>
   While many were enjoying the black tie affair that also featured
singer Freda Payne and comedian Lewis Dix, most said they came not
for the partying but to support bringing more blacks into politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're really on the brink of disaster in the 21st
century,'' Belafonte said. ''Despite a booming economy ... there
are a lot of disadvantaged people left out of the process. And most
of them are black.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Conga Room, a Hollywood nightclub and restaurant,
convention goers were invited to listen to Latin music with Joe
Andrew, the Democratic party's national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   A day after Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., bowed to pressure
from the Democratic Party to cancel her Playboy mansion fund-raiser
for Hispanic voter registration, Hugh Hefner opened his lavish home
for the convention-attending news media.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit-eared Playboy bunnies mingled with the media's most
influential, including CBS' Bryant Gumbel and comic talk show host
Bill Maher.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had someone ask me if I had to get CBS' permission to be
here. My answer was no, and I would never ask for permission,''
Gumbel said, standing next to a Playmates' swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Maher, host of ABC's ''Politically Incorrect,'' joked that he
should have read his invitation more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I'd come here to relax,'' he said. ''I didn't
realize there would be all these journalists and I'd be working.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 guests, Arianna Huffington called the event a ''true
trade gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like everybody I've ever worked with (in the media)
is here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez caused consternation at the top levels of the Democratic
Party by deciding to hold the fund-raiser at Hefner's estate, famed
for its scantily clad women. She changed her mind Friday only after
convention organizers revoked her invitation to address the
gathering next week.
</P>
<P>
   Her speaking slot at the convention was reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   When ''Soul Train'' executive producer Don Cornelius calls, the
performers will come.
</P>
<P>
   Singer-songwriter Brian McKnight said after the negative
publicity he received for his performance at the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia, he swore off future political
events.
</P>
<P>
   ''But when Don calls, you come,'' McKnight said.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight said he originally was supposed to sing following
President Clinton's speech at the Democratic convention Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''But after the Republican convention, they called and said we
don't need you anymore,'' he said. ''If I performed in China, they
wouldn't call me a communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a convention gig, McKnight, who said he doesn't vote,
performed Sunday at the African-American Committee 2000 and Beyond
concert hosted by Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He said his performance at the Los Angeles Sports Arena was
designed to help delegates relax.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody needs a chance to let it all hang out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   Actor Wayne Brady was star-struck.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the front row of the Divas and Kings concert, held
Sunday for Democratic convention delegates at the Los Angeles
Sports Arena, he said he was tied up in knots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm kind of embarrassed. If they looked down they could see me
saying 'I love you,''' said Brady, who is a cast member with Drew
Carry on ABC-TV's ''Who's Line Is It Anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady said that backstage he was afraid to talk with the
performers, who included Patti LaBelle and Luther Vandross.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really afraid if I do I'd ... make a big idiot of
myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he planned to try to give LaBelle a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LaBelle lost her toe ring and decided to sing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through her rendition of ''Somewhere Over the Rainbow,''
the diva told the audience in song that the ring had fallen off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, I just lost my toe ring,'' she sang. ''My girl just gave
it to me tonight. I've got to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   As LaBelle continued to sing, she searched the stage for the
missing jewelry. She joked with the audience that it was covering a
corn on her toe. A stagehand who came onstage while she was singing
found the ring as she was finishing her number.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, thank you. I wasn't leaving this stage without it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Following a three-year hiatus, R&AMP;B singing group Boyz II Men is
back to making music. This time at the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The four singers, who burst onto the music scene more than a
decade ago, took the last three years off.
</P>
<P>
   The group members said they performing at various convention
functions, including singing the National Anthem before Al Gore's
acceptance speech Thursday night to get the word out on two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Shawn Stockton said the group believed young people
needed to get involved and vote. But he also said the group's
appearance was to help boost its first new album in more than four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want people to hear us. We just want to entertain people''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
