<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Role in Gore Race Mulled  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- There are two ways President Clinton can help
Al Gore win the White House after making a splashy, opening-night
speech at the Democratic convention Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One is to race around and campaign hard for Gore. The other is
to stay home and hope voters forget about him.
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates are decidedly mixed about what the
president should do.
</P>
<P>
   In some places it would help to have Clinton boast about peace
and prosperity, delegates said. But in others he would cast a cloud
because of his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if Clinton coming into Kentucky will be much of a
help to Al Gore's campaign,'' said state AFL-CIO president Bill
Londrigan. The president's stands on tobacco and guns are not
popular, added Robertson County tax assessor Karen Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia state Rep. Doug Teper of Atlanta said Clinton should
limit his campaigning. ''I don't think he sells for this race,''
Teper said. Paula Martinez, the mother of five in Carlisle, Iowa,
said Clinton wants to help ''but the negative image is there and it
is really sad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Pocan, a businessman and member of the Wisconsin state
Legislature, said, ''I have heard a lot of people say if Bill
Clinton was running again they'd vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The president would be welcome in Florida, said Bob Poe,
chairman of the state Democratic Party. ''Clinton's a great
campaigner,'' Poe said. ''He still has high marks and his record as
president is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Anne Bowman, a state representative from Portland, Ore.,
said, ''I really think Al Gore needs to have Clinton come to Oregon
to remind people about how much this administration has done for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Thomas, an attorney in Tallulah, La., said, ''In certain
areas like New Orleans he will campaign for him and it will work
because Clinton is still strong in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   As the convention opens, there's as much buzz about Clinton as
there is about Gore, who's supposed to be the star of the show.
</P>
<P>
   How can Gore emerge from Clinton's shadow -- particularly after
the president gives a convention speech that's sure to ignite a
frenzied celebration?
</P>
<P>
   ''He should know that he's the opening act and Gore's the
headliner now,'' said Vanderbilt University political scientist
Bruce Oppenheimer. ''The opening act gets the crowd enthused,
enjoying themselves, but doesn't step on the headliner.'' Clinton
should leave the memorable lines for Gore, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats are grumbling that Clinton is grabbing the
attention and soaking up campaign cash that the vice president
could use. Clinton and his Senate candidate-wife Hillary arrived
Friday for four days of Hollywood parties and tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Behind in the polls and still struggling to introduce himself to
the nation, Gore needs a spark for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If California becomes a battleground, the president could help,
drawing on his friends in Hollywood and his strong popularity here.
Washington state and Oregon are obvious targets for Clinton's
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which voters say they do not like political rancor,
Clinton has a freer hand than Gore to attack Republicans. He also
can energize voters in targeted areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a mistake to put him on the shelf,'' said
Democratic consultant Jim Duffy. ''He's too good. Yes, he's
controversial but you're not winning on your own. Pick your spots
where you use him. Certainly in Chicago, Detroit, Cleveland,
Pittsburgh, Philadelphia. Why wouldn't you put him in those big
urban areas where you've got labor, where you've got blacks, where
you've got some liberal progressive types?''
</P>
<P>
   But Duffy said Gore has to use Clinton judiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ''So you've got to learn to say, 'Bill, please just talk about
the future and what Al can do to continue the work that you have
done,'' Duffy said. ''And keep it on the issues. And by the way,
please don't get into any more of your personal redemption. If you
want to be an evangelist, wait until you leave office.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton caused a stir Thursday when, in a meeting with
evangelical ministers, he expressed remorse for his affair with
Lewinsky -- remarks that resurrected an episode that Americans would
like to forget. It also stole headlines from Gore and his running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press, White House Chief of
Staff John Podesta said his boss will use his convention speech to
counter GOP criticisms that he and Gore squandered eight years in
office and accomplished little.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Republicans may have had a little amnesia about where
things stood in 1992 and I think the president will be happy to
remind people about that and remind people of the kinds of efforts
he's made,'' Podesta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 0243 </TRAILER>
