<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 6; Nasdaq Loses 20  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Monday as wary investors
tried to reconcile positive economic news with fears of a
second-half earnings slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 5.86 at 11,033.66.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.73 at 1,470.11, and
the Nasdaq composite index was down 19.94 at 3,769.53.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks rose on Friday on an inflation report that
showed that wholesale prices remained virtually the same in July
after a huge jump in June caused by soaring energy costs. The Dow
index closed above 11,000 for the first time since April 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said its Producer Price Index, which
measures inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was
flat in July, a significant easing of price pressures following a
hefty 0.6 percent surge in June.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have kept pressure on technology stocks, however, in
the wake of warnings from some widely held companies that earnings
could fall in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 99.32 million shares, down
from Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.63 at 509.64.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.23 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.05 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.57 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.76 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
