<HEADLINE> Paraguay Election Results Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- The release of final results in
Paraguay's vote for a successor to slain vice president Luis Argana
has been postponed for days because the balloting was so close,
election officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials suspended the release of official results late Sunday
after 90 percent of the vote had been counted, saying they wanted
to closely monitor the tallying of the remaining ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the difference is very slim, we will need to verify the
vote to avoid any possibilities of fraud,'' said Carlos Maria
Ljubetic, a spokesman for the election board. ''We will have a
definitive result in the next 10 to 12 days,''
</P>
<P>
   Early returns showed no clear leader in the vote for a successor
to Argana -- an election that could test the South American nation's
weak democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidate Julio Cesar Franco appeared to hold a slim
lead in early returns Sunday, with 47.77 percent of the ballot.
Felix Argana, the son of the slain vice president, had 46.93
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the results hold, it would be the first electoral defeat for
the ruling Colorado Party, which has dominated politics for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million Paraguayans voted Sunday for a successor to
Argana, whose assassination in March 1999 forced former President
Raul Cubas to resign and seek political asylum in Brazil. Cubas was
suspected of being involved in Argana's death.
</P>
<P>
   The new vice president will join President Luis Gonzalez Macchi,
the former Senate president who took office after Cubas was ousted
and who has seen his popularity plummet with an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Although tension had been predicted on election day, officials
reported no violence during the voting. Six people were killed in
rioting that followed Argana's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a balcony at Liberal Party headquarters, the
48-year-old Franco told some 5,000 supporters they were on the
verge of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people have spoken in free, democratic and transparent
elections,'' he bellowed into a microphone, his neck wrapped in the
party's royal blue flag. ''I want to ask you all to vigilant as
they count the final votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, a doctor, has suggested that if elected he would work to
have Macchi removed from office. A faction of the Colorado Party
has been strongly critical of Macchi, and Franco could look for
their support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Faces were long at Colorado party headquarters. Argana, 43, had
earlier declared victory, citing his own party's exit polls. But in
the evening, he offered no comment. The Colorado party has ruled
Paraguay since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Argana and his supporters appeared confident at
their party office, festooned in the Colorado colors of red and
white.
</P>
<P>
   An architect and Asuncion city councilman, the 43-year-old voted
Sunday morning after visiting his father's tomb. He has said he
does not intend to overshadow Macchi but to be a stabilizing force
in his troubled administration.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi's popularity has dipped to less than 20 percent as
Paraguay struggles through a grinding recession. He has refused to
hold an election to validate his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Argana's murder remains unsolved, although a
Paraguayan judge has accused Lino Oviedo, an army chief and former
political ally of Cubas, of masterminding the killing.
</P>
<P>
   A third candidate, Ricardo Buman of the Humanist Party, was
considered a long shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 1112 </TRAILER>
