<HEADLINE> N., S. Korea Prepare for Reunions  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Frail husbands and wives meeting for
the first time in more than 50 years. Sons and daughters greeting
parents lost across a militarized border. Separated in childhood,
brothers and sisters, now elderly, embracing yet again.
</P>
<P>
   In an event that promises tears of joy and anguish for Koreans
on both sides of the border, a tiny fraction of the victims of a
Cold War-era conflict that separated millions will reunite briefly
with loved ones this week.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred people from North Korea were to fly to South Korea
on Tuesday, and an equal number of South Koreans will head north in
the most emotionally charged dividend of a historic June summit
between the two countries' leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't describe how I feel,'' Choi Soon-nam, an 87-year-old
South Korean who will meet her 60-year-old son in the communist
North, said Monday. ''I have so much to say to him. But when I
actually see him, I may not be able to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-day reunion is as much a political event as it is a
humanitarian one, a good will gesture between two nations that have
taken bigger steps toward reconciliation in the last two months
than at any time since the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   There will be euphoria, and also reminders of the pain and
permanent loss of separation, when the separated family members
meet under the glare of television lights in a Seoul convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   A 99-year-old South Korean is unlikely to recognize her son from
the North because she is mentally ill. A 61-year-old man was so
excited to hear his older brother would visit the South that he
fell ill and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jang-soo, a 68-year-old former North Korean soldier who was
captured in the Korean War and settled in the South, will meet his
two sisters when he travels to the North's capital of Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I get there, I want to find out when my mother passed
away. I told my mother I would return in three years. And it became
50 years,'' said Kim, whose gifts for his family include rings,
watches, socks, underwear and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions are a pressing issue because many aging family
members have only a few years left to see relatives. Many people
have died without making contact with relatives. There is no mail,
telephone or other direct means of communication between private
citizens in the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul and Pyongyang organized family reunions in 1985, but
political acrimony undercut efforts to organize another round. Ties
remain so delicate that family members who will travel north are
under strict instructions to avoid talking politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please be careful in what you say and how you behave,'' Yang
Young-shik, vice minister of Seoul's Unification Ministry, told
family members at a briefing at a five-star hotel Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at the hotel, which will house the North Korean group,
have removed imported Western goods such as liquor and replaced
them with traditional Korean drinks to avoid unsettling their
guests.
</P>
<P>
   At a banquet Monday at the Blue House presidential residence,
President Kim Dae-jung told the family members -- some carrying
canes or stooped with age -- that reconciliation and eventual
reunification would be a lengthy process. But he said the reunions
this week would not be an isolated event.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will have more visits, open a permanent reunion office,
exchange letters and visit our hometowns,'' Kim said. ''Whether you
settle in the North or South, you must be reunited with your
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The government gave $500 to each family member to buy gifts for
relatives in the impoverished North, Kim announced.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rapprochement between the Koreas, uneasiness lingers
in the South over apparent political use of the event by the North.
</P>
<P>
   While South Korea chose its 100 finalists for the reunions
through a computer lottery, the North Korean list includes a
renowned poet, a painter, a film maker, a scientist and other
celebrated people. And all the Northern visitors are natives of
South Korea who defected to the North.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean critics said loyalty to the communist system
appeared to be the most important criterion for getting on the
North's list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
