<HEADLINE> Diplomats Seek Meeting in Yugoslavia  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Diplomats on Monday protested
Yugoslav authorities' refusal to let them meet in private with two
Britons and two Canadians jailed by the Yugoslav army, which calls
them suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, countries allow diplomats to meet privately with
detainees. But ''this is not a full-fledged consular access because
it's not in private and it's always in the presence of an
investigator,'' said British diplomat Robert Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav army officials say they found explosives-related
materials in the men's car when it was stopped Aug. 1 at an army
checkpoint in Montenegro, which along with Serbia makes up
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The men had been working in the Serbian province of Kosovo,
occupied by NATO-led peacekeepers after NATO's 78-day bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia last year. They four said they were in
Montenegro for vacation.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty of terrorism, they could be sentenced to up to
15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Britons Adrian Prangnell and John Yore trained police officers
in Kosovo for the Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe. Canadian Shaun Going and his nephew Liam Hall were
rebuilding homes damaged by the war, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The men have not yet been formally charged and have denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Pretrial proceedings continued Monday at a military court in
Belgrade, a defense attorney told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on the testimonies we've heard so far, they have no
case,'' attorney Djordje Djurisic said. ''The investigation is now
over, it's now up to the military prosecutor to decide whether to
file charges or drop the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Canadian diplomat Craig Bale met with the four men
Monday for the fourth time since they were detained. ''They are
fine, they are coping and are very grateful for the support they
are getting,'' from family and friends, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney defending the two Canadians, Ivan Jankovic, told
reporters that he feared the ''decision whether to file charges
will not be judicially independent but a political'' one.
</P>
<P>
   They arrests followed Yugoslav allegations that NATO has hired
mercenaries to detain fugitive war crimes suspects. Milosevic has
been indicted by the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands, on charges he is responsible for atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
