<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Braces for More Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By NEELESH MISRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Security forces turned Srinagar into a
garrison town Monday, the eve of India's independence day, as they
sought to prevent further rebel attacks like the car bombing that
killed 14 people last week.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soldiers, paramilitary troops and police spread
across Srinagar, summer capital of disputed Kashmir, and other
areas vulnerable to attack by Islamic guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a war zone. We are taking all precautions,'' said
Kul Bhushan Jandial, the state government's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is the focus of an Islamic insurgency that has killed at
least 25,000 people in the past 11 years. More than a dozen
militant groups have been fighting Indian forces, demanding
independence or Kashmir's merger with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, three soldiers and five civilians were wounded in two
incidents in the Himalayan state. The attacks came a day after two
land mines killed six soldiers, 10 rebels died in gun battles with
government troops and three explosions injured 42 other people.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpshooters took positions Monday overlooking Bakshi Stadium
in Srinagar, where Chief Minister Farooq Abdullah, Kashmir's top
elected leader, was to give a speech Tuesday. Police fear rocket
attacks on the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers wearing bulletproof vests and helmets inspected cars at
checkpoints and looked for bombs under cars in parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cars have been stolen. Some of them could be used by the
militants in such attacks,'' Chavang Phunsog, Kashmir's principal
home secretary, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Girish Chandra Saxena, the federal representative in
Kashmir, acknowledged human rights excesses by security forces in
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ''This problem is inherent in the prevailing circumstances,
which have been created by the terrorist and their foreign
mentors,'' Saxenna said in a statement. He urged security forces to
''take care to minimize civilian casualties or losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Separatist guerrillas in the Kashmir Valley have observed
India's Independence Day as a ''Black Day'' since 1989. India
accuses neighboring Pakistan of fomenting and backing the
militancy, a charge Pakistan denies.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan President Rafiq Tarar said in an address Monday -- the
day his country celebrates independence from Britain -- that
Islamabad would continue to support the struggle in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, hopes for peace rose when Hezb-ul Mujahedeeen, the
main militant group, announced a cease-fire and the Indian
government responded by suspending its offensives.
</P>
<P>
   But peace talks fell through when India refused a demand to
include Pakistan in the discussions. The Hezb-ul Mujahedeen broke
the cease-fire with a car bomb in downtown Srinagar that killed 13
soldiers and a journalist and wounded 25 other people Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   India holds two-thirds of Kashmir and Pakistan the rest. The
hostile nuclear armed neighbors have fought two wars for control of
Kashmir since they won independence from Britain in 1947.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
