<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Effort to understand 1776 battle leads to charting Lake Champlain site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VALCOUR, N.Y. (AP) - Divers have begun charting a historic New
York lake that was the site of a 1776 battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Weve already completed an exhaustive examination of the
historical and archival records of the battle,'' said Arthur Cohn,
executive director for the Lake Champlain Maritime Museum in Basin
Harbor, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now were adding an archaeological study to that history to
better understand and preserve the area for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Using metal detectors, about 14 divers are mapping the silty
lake bottom, identifying any objects they might pick up buried in
the mud around Valcour, about 140 miles north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''Its a pretty tedious but straightforward process,'' Cohn said.
''If you think about a battlefield above ground, were trying to do
that same kind of study under water by determining what objects
might still remain there.''
</P>
<P>
   Divers are cataloging the items they find but all objects are
staying on the lake bottom, organizers said. The cool, fresh water
and silty bottom are perfect environments for protecting the
artifacts until a plan can be devised for preserving and displaying
them in a public setting.
</P>
<P>
   ''As divers, we get to look at these objects first-hand,'' said
former Plattsburgh City Police Chief Matthew Booth, one of the
volunteer divers working on the project. ''But if we can recover
these artifacts and put them on display, then everyone gets a
chance to appreciate and study them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They belong to everybody, not just the city or county or state
of New York,'' Booth said. ''This is a regional effort. Lake
Champlain is a corridor where a lot of important history took
place. Its everybodys job to preserve that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to American and British cannons, bayonets and
ammunition, the survey is also identifying the human aspect of the
battle. For instance, one of the objects surveyed is a cartridge
box that still has part of the leather cover and clear initials,
''GMB,'' of the man who used it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Its very exciting,'' added Tony Tyrell, who works for the
Department of Environmental Conservation as the Valcour Island
caretaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''This area almost takes on a sacred graveyard atmosphere,'' he
said. These men were our forefathers. Theyre why were not paying
tea taxes today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-14-00 1402 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000814.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freed Colombia Hostage Has 1 Regret  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- American biologist John Lynch emerged
from captivity at the hands of leftist rebels with one regret: he
did not find a caecilian -- a giant wormlike creature he's been
hunting for years in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   To one of the world's authorities on amphibians, Colombia is
heaven; it has more of the creatures than anywhere else. But with
guerrilla armies, government forces and right-wing paramilitaries
battling for control of this South American nation, it's also one
of the world's most dangerous places.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Iowa native's quest to find new species sometimes
lands him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scrape for the former University of Nebraska
professor came last week, when guerrillas snatched him and 25
Colombian colleagues in the Andes Mountains and ''detained'' them
for three days until freeing them Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extensive interview since being released, Lynch
told The Associated Press on Sunday that rebels of the National
Liberation Army, or ELN, had treated his group well, and in fact
may have been worried about their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities who contracted the scientific team to catalog flora
and fauna in the Andes in western Colombia had neglected to let the
ELN, which controls the area, know the group was coming, said
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   When the group arrived Aug. 7 in the village of San Miguel, the
rebels came and asked what the group was doing. The team, composed
of professors and students from the National University in Bogota,
was frisked for weapons. Then the rebels left.
</P>
<P>
   They returned Wednesday and told the scientific team to
accompany them into the virgin forest. For hours, they stumbled
along in the dark. The rain forest became alive with the sounds of
nocturnal animals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could hear the frogs calling, and thought, 'Damn, there's no
way to catch them,''' Lynch recalled.
</P>
<P>
   At a rebel camp deep in the forest, the weary team collapsed
into sleeping bags. The next day, the local ELN boss, Comandante
Javier, told the group they were not kidnapped but ''detained.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought at first it was a pretty silly distinction,'' Lynch
said. ''As a group we discussed what to do. We couldn't try to run
because some of us were not in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientists decided to sit tight. Javier then allowed them to
collect biological samples, under guard.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch had been questioning the rebels about the presence of
caecilians, nocturnal creatures that are as thick as a man's index
finger and can grow to more than four feet long. He had caught
dozens over the years, but the rebels described a different
variant: a reddish one with white rings.
</P>
<P>
   If he could find one, Lynch might be discovering a new type of
amphibian. He has already found dozens.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old scientist's blue eyes flash as he discusses
caecilians. Last year, he trekked into the countryside in search of
them, only to be kidnapped by the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia -- the nation's other rebel group -- and held for a day and
a half before being freed.
</P>
<P>
   Flashlight in hand, Lynch planned last Friday night to hunt for
the muscular burrowing creatures. But then Javier announced that
the group was being released that evening.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists trudged back to San Miguel, where they were
turned over to local government, church and human rights officials.
</P>
<P>
   ELN commander Nicolas Rodriguez said his forces detained the
scientists for their own safety, a claim Lynch believes.
</P>
<P>
   Paramilitary forces in the area execute suspected rebel
collaborators. Government counterinsurgency troops roam the forest,
and could mistake a scientist for a rebel, Lynch said. The ELN said
it did not want to be blamed if a scientist wound up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Given his two short stretches of captivity with Colombia's two
rebel groups, Lynch has been lucky. Rebels have executed
foreigners, or held them for lengthy periods.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynch, an associate professor at the National University and
a curator at its natural history museum, says he won't let the
dangers of Colombia deter his mission to add to the 650 types of
amphibians known to exist in Colombia. On Monday, he was already
back at work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love tramping around in the trackless cloud forest,'' he
said. ''I'm not going to stop going out. I want to help reveal to
the world that the Andes in this country is a gold mine in
amphibians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
