<HEADLINE> Ivory Coast Opposition Leader To Run  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- One of Ivory Coast's main opposition
leaders officially launched his candidacy for president Monday
despite questions about his eligibility for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Alassane Dramane Ouattara, leader of the Rally of the
Republicans, accepted his party's nomination for Sept. 17 elections
before a crowd of cheering thousands at the luxury Hotel Ivoire in
the country's commercial capital, Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ivorians, what I offer you for today and for tomorrow is to
build together, side by side, hand in hand, the great nation that
we all deserve,'' Ouattara said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes at a time of mounting tension in Ivory
Coast, which until a Christmas Eve military coup was considered a
bastion of stability in volatile West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Although the December takeover was initially popular among many
Ivorians, who had grown tired of corruption and ethnic favoritism
under ousted President Henri Konan Bedie, many have since become
disillusioned with the new military regime.
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled soldiers have mutinied twice over bonuses and perks
they say they were promised for supporting the coup. There has been
no improvement in the economy, which has been hobbled by plummeting
prices for the country's main exports, cocoa and coffee. And many
believe the new government's policies are fueling the same ethnic
tensions that divided the country under Bedie.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute amendment to the country's new constitution, which
is to guide the country's return to civilian rule, stipulates that
both parents of presidential candidates must be ''of Ivorian
origin'' -- a change widely believed to be aimed at excluding
Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara, a former prime minister and top official with the
International Monetary Fund, says he is not affected by the change
because both his parents were Ivorian. But his opponents insist
they were from Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara's followers have threatened unrest if their leader is
not allowed to run.
</P>
<P>
   Junta leader Gen. Robert Guei is also seeking nomination -- by
the former ruling Democratic Party of Ivory Coast, or PDCI, which
his soldiers ousted from power.
</P>
<P>
   Guei's moves to remain in power have alienated some of his
military allies, according to news reports. The reports say some
junta members are asking that Guei resign if he wants to run in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie, who fled to France after the coup, has already been
nominated as the PDCI candidate at a conference organized by party
members in Paris. However, that move was condemned by party
officials in Ivory Coast who said the decision must be made here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
