<DOCNO> APW20000814.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman signs tax credit bill to aid working poor  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Boasting that her 38th tax cut aids the
working poor, Gov. Christie Whitman signed into law a tax credit
designed to eventually give low-income families up to $3,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is especially pleasing to me because this is especially
directed at those out there working to make ends meet,'' Whitman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Families earning less than $20,000 a year can now apply for New
Jersey's version of the Earned Income Tax Credit, similar to the
federal program of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Families in that income bracket are exempt from paying state
income taxes and often receive refunds for the taxes withheld from
their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill Whitman signed, the tax credit will translate
into an additional refund.
</P>
<P>
   About 280,000 families are eligible this year. The state expects
240,000 families to apply this year and receive checks for up to
$349. By 2003, a family with two or more children would get $3,000
by taking advantage of the state and federal tax programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration will spend $45 million this year and
$69.7 million next year in state and federal money to pay for the
tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag rises to $84.1 million in 2002 and to $99.5
million in 2003, its final year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit boosts efforts made by the state's
welfare-to-work policies, Whitman said. It helps poor families
while maintaining ''the dignity of work,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They share in that benefit, and they share that desire to stay
in the work force,'' Whitman said. ''It will reward hard work and
encourage self-sufficiency''
</P>
<P>
   Social advocates who pushed for the tax credit praised the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''The administration and the Legislature have done more than any
in memory to aid the working poor,'' said Melville D. Miller Jr.,
president of the Legal Services of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued last month, Miller's group claimed the
state's poverty rate is 9.1 percent, based on data collected
primarily in 1997. A single-parent family of three making $13,133
would be at the poverty line, using federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, roughly 731,000 people in the state were considered to
be living in poverty, according to the report. That was about
50,000 more than in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is up to all of us to continue to work to aid the poor in
New Jersey,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   That work includes ''fine tuning'' this tax credit to include
single people, Miller said. Other aid organizations have pushed to
have more relief for families with more children. The program gives
the same benefit to families with two or more children.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she is willing to work on the tax program and said
the credit for singles is a priority. So is the possibility of
raising the $20,000 income limit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are willing to go back and work with the advocacy groups,''
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was good news to Sandra Latson, a single mother of
three, who said the check from the state will help. She said she
would ''definitely start a savings account and not just have a
checking account.''
</P>
<P>
   The East Orange resident now works at a hotel at Newark
International Airport. October marks the first year she's been off
welfare, Latson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just feels good to be out there with working people, going
to day care with other working mothers,'' Latson said. ''It's hard,
being that I'm a single parent, but it feels good to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
