<HEADLINE> Ancient Artifacts Recovered at Port  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Customs officials and archaeologists have
intercepted a crate containing ancient artifacts that apparently
had been destined for the underground antiquities market abroad,
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts date from 3000 B.C. to 1000 A.D. and include
coins, pottery, bronze items and small statues. They were looted
from archaeological digs around Israel, Yoav Sarhi, an
archaeologist with Israel's Antiquities Board, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on an anonymous tip, archaeologists alerted authorities
at Haifa port about the crate before it was loaded onto a ship
destined for the United States, Sarhi said. He would not specify
the exact date of the interception, saying only that it was a ''few
days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials have suspects in the attempted smuggling but do not
want to release names while the case is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Sarhi said the plundering of historical sites is a common
occurrence in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is the only country in the Middle East that allows
merchants to trade in antiquities, he said. As a result, robbers
have an ample market for their stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists and Israeli lawmakers are working to rewrite laws
aimed at shutting down the trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
