<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders Hold Summit on Congo War  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRED MULENGA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- Ten African presidents gathered Monday in
Zambia for an urgent push to salvage the crumbling Congo peace
accord and to pave the way for the deployment of U.N. peacekeepers
in the war-wracked country.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese President Laurent Kabila, who angered even his close
allies by staying away from a regional economic summit last week,
was the last of the 10 to arrive. Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba is the chief mediator for the one-day talks.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo broke out in August 1998, with rebels
backed by Rwanda and Uganda accusing Kabila of corruption and of
harboring Hutu militiamen who fled Rwanda after committing genocide
there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and his allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- signed a
cease-fire agreement last year with Rwanda, Uganda and the rebels.
But fighting has intensified in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Monday included the leaders of all the warring
parties except Angola, as well as other African leaders. Angola
sent Defense Minister Kundi Paiwama because President Eduardo dos
Santos seldom leaves the country, which is gripped by its own civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   The warring parties and Chiluba were to discuss ways to maintain
the cease-fire, to create conditions for military disengagement and
to facilitate Congo's internal political dialogue between the
rebels and the government, Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary general of
the Organization of African Unity, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am optimistic. We have been dealing with the real issues,''
he said after nearly seven hours of closed-door meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila was expected to come under pressure to accept deployment
of 5,537 U.N. observers and troops. The Security Council mandate
for the force is up for renewal at the end of this month and likely
will be suspended if Kabila continues to obstruct deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila is also expected to be pressured into accepting former
Botswana President Sir Ketumile Masire as a facilitator for an
internal political dialogue between Kabila and Congolese rebels.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what role rebel leaders would play
in the Lusaka talks. Past meetings have been split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, aided by Rwanda and Uganda, ousted dictator Mobutu Sese
Seko in 1997 in the vast mineral-rich central African nation then
known as Zaire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
