<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile virus found in Rhode Island  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID RISING
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARWICK, R.I. (AP) - Environmental officials announced plans
Monday to spray insecticide in a two-mile radius where researchers
found a dead crow with West Nile virus, the first time the
potentially fatal disease was detected in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Four trucks will spray more than 200 miles of streets in Warwick
and Cranston, including the area where the state prison is located.
Wind and rain will delay the effort until Tuesday night the
earliest, officials said. A warning truck will drive the route
first, alerting residents to stay indoors during the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   The bird, found last Tuesday, was tested at the University of
Rhode Island virology laboratory and the results came back late
Sunday. State environmental officials said they expected to find
the disease in Rhode Island, since it already has been detected in
Connecticut and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would have been a bizarre fluke of nature if we had been
skipped,'' said Malcolm Grant, the Department of Environmental
Management's associate director for natural resources management.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Rhode Island has been infected. Three New York City
residents contracted the illness this summer and have been
recovering.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lyme disease, carried by ticks, and the mosquito borne
eastern equine encephalitis, which was first spotted in the state
several years ago, West Nile virus appears to be here to stay. Alan
Gettman, a state scientist, said the virus has already proven it
can withstand a northern winter.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is spreading in the New England region, and certainly seems
to be establishing itself,'' Gettman said.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the summer, Rhode Island has been distributing
larvicide to communities to kill mosquitoes before they fly.
Environmental and health officials also launched an extensive
public education campaign to alert residents to the potential risk.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is commonly carried by bloodsucking mosquitoes, which
transmit the disease through bites. Infection may result in
encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain, or meningitis, an
inflammation of the brain's lining and the spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   The spraying program that will soon be undertaken is the
response recommended by the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   The spraying will significantly reduce the mosquito population,
but Grant said people should still take their own precautions, like
using bug spray outside, covering baby carriages with mosquito
netting, and removing standing water - where mosquitos breed - from
their property.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are doing will help, but what the individual does will
ensure their safety,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has set up a hot line, 788-3698, for people to call if
they find dead birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should be reporting the birds that are behaving
abnormally, staggering, not flying away when you approach them -
anything that would suggest a neurological problem,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, during the first known appearance of the West Nile
virus in the Western Hemisphere, seven people died and 62 others
were infected in the New York metropolitan area, prompting the city
to undertake an aerial and ground spraying campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most West Nile virus infections cause few or no symptoms. Only
about 1 in 300 people become seriously ill and just a small number
die.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known to affect cats or dogs, but was responsible for
the deaths of several horses in New York last year, Gettman said.
</P>
<P>
   The virus also has been found this year in New Jersey and
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus is named after the West Nile region of
Uganda, where it was first isolated in 1937. West Nile virus is
most commonly found in Africa, West Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   www.state.ri.us/dem
</P>
<P>
   www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/westnile/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   www.health.state.ri.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
