<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Begins Land Dispute Trial  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Three police officers charged with
killing 10 squatters in one of Brazil's bloodiest land conflicts
pleaded innocent Monday, telling a judge they acted in
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Airton Ramos de Morais, Jose Emilio da Silva Evangelista and
Daniel da Silva Furtado are each charged with three counts of
homicide in a 1995 clash that left 10 squatters and two police
officers dead near the southern Amazon town of Corumbiara some
1,800 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening testimony, each of the officers told Judge
Sandra Santos that they had traveled to the Santa Eliana ranch with
the intention of forcing out 500 squatters by cutting off their
water and waiting them out.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early hours of Aug. 9, 1995, commanding officers
ordered them to advance on the squatters and a shootout ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fired, my companions fired, the special operations commandos
fired. It was a real confrontation,'' said Furtado, ''It wasn't
until it ended that I knew what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege some 300 police encircled the camp around 2
a.m., tossed in tear gas and stun grenades and invaded the
settlement with guns blazing.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy reports later showed that of the 10 squatters killed,
seven were shot point blank in the face, neck, chest and back. One
victim, Ercilio Oliveira de Campos, was shot 19 times. Another, who
was not identified, was shot 12 times in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the police argue they were met with gunfire as they
arrived to carry out an eviction order. Squatters had asked the
government to carve out a small plot for them, but local ranchers
insisted on expelling them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police only reacted after the killing of two policemen in
an area where there were 190 officers against 1,200 landless,''
Marcos Soares, a lawyer for the police told reporters before the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments were expected later in the week and a verdict
was likely either Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Security around the courthouse was tight with hundreds of police
outside and federal agents inside.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is the first in a series of such proceedings expected
to last through early September. Thirteen officers and two
squatters will be tried.
</P>
<P>
   The case has taken five years to get to trial due to the complex
nature of the country's justice system. Some say the politically
explosive nature of the case has also dragged the matter out.
</P>
<P>
   Unequal land distribution is at the root of rural violence in
Brazil, where 90 percent of the land belongs to 20 percent of the
people, and the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade more than 1,000 people have lost their
lives in land disputes in Brazil, according to the Land Pastoral, a
Catholic group that advocates land reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 1641 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000814.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury awards GE Capital $133 million in suit against DirecTV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - A federal jury awarded GE Capital a
whopping $133 million after the company sued DirecTV to recover
losses on consumer loans for satellite dishes and converter boxes.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV, the country's top satellite TV broadcaster, hired GE
Capital in 1995 to manage a consumer-financing program for the
purchase of DirecTV satellite dishes and boxes. DirecTV was eager
to sign up new subscribers in the highly competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies created the ''EZ Approval'' program for
equipment financing.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Byman, GE's lead counsel during a six-week trial, said
DirecTV agreed in their contract to reimburse GE Capital if
consumers defaulted on their loans.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital sued DirecTV in 1997, estimating the total in bad
loans at about $150 million, Byman said. DirecTV had paid about $40
million before trial, so by the time the case got to court GE
Capital was seeking about $118 million in losses plus another $40
million in interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV countersued, asking for $45 million in damages, alleging
that GE Capital fraudulently induced DirecTV to enter into the
program by misrepresenting its abilities to provide accurate credit
scores for loan applicants and other services.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded GE Capital $133 million on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial a former DirecTV sales representative testified
for GE Capital that he was instructed to inflate the credit
qualifications of potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''These companies started from ground zero ... so in order to
keep investors happy, in order to keep the company afloat, you had
to show that you were building up the subscribers that would
someday make these companies profitable,'' Byman said in an
interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher A. Murphy, DirecTV's assistant general counsel,
could not be reached for comment Monday. He told the Connecticut
Law Tribune that the company will appeal the verdict based on
material Senior U.S. District Judge Peter Dorsey refused to let
into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said GE's patented process for measuring credit risks was
fundamentally flawed and directly led to the losses.
</P>
<P>
   DirecTV's parent company, Hughes Electronics Corp., issued a
press release after the verdict, contending that the losses were
caused by GE Capital's failure to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very disappointed in the verdict and do not believe
that it is supported at all by the facts. We will appeal and are
confident that the verdict will be overturned,'' said Robert M.
Hall, senior vice president and general counsel of DirecTV
Enterprises Inc.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital has filed a motion asking the judge to award an
additional $47 million in interest, based on an offer it made in
1999 to settle the case for $95 million, Byman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
