<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With: BC-NJ--Tax Credits  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key points in how New Jersey's Earned Income Tax
Credit will
work:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Families earning under $20,000 can apply. About 280,000 are
estimated to be eligible. State officials expect about 240,000, or
80 percent, to apply.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit applies to income earned after Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Residents apply for the credit by completing the worksheet
included with their 2000 New Jersey Income Tax Return.
</P>
<P>
   Those earning under $20,000 are exempt from state income taxes.
This income credit offsets any taxes owed. Whatever amount exceeds
the tax owed by the family is sent to them as a refund check. This
credit is in addition to any state tax refund.
</P>
<P>
   Checks are mailed to residents directly just as other tax refund
checks.
</P>
<P>
   In this tax year, families with two or more children with
incomes of $10,000 will see a credit of $394.
</P>
<P>
   For families with an income of $15,000, the credit is $338.
</P>
<P>
   For families with an income of $20,000, the credit is $229.
</P>
<P>
   In 2003, when the tax credit program is phased in, families
earning $10,000 will see a credit of $823.
</P>
<P>
   For families with an income of $15,000, the credit is $707.
</P>
<P>
   For families with an income of $20,000, the credit is $480.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate that when combined with the federal
income tax credit, families can see up to $3,000 refunded.
</P>
<P>
   The program is expected to cost $44.9 million this year and
$99.5 million by 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
