<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New England ponders 'Lieberman effect' on race  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Vice President Al Gore grew up in
Washington and Tennessee. But with the help of Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, Gore is counting on a region far from Nashville
or the nation's capital to help him win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   A New England sweep by Gore and Lieberman would help Democrats
offset expected Republican domination of the South and Texas, as
the two parties prepare for a presidential race that experts
predict will be extremely close.
</P>
<P>
   Geography was probably not Gore's first consideration in
selecting Lieberman, a moderate who has won praise from both sides
of the aisle for his personal integrity and public condemnation of
President Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   But with Lieberman on board, a Democratic strategy emphasizing
the Northeast makes sense, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the six New England states have 35 electoral votes -
more than enough to offset the 32 votes in Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's home state and a good start toward the 270 electoral votes
needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   When New York's 33 delegates are added, the Northeast becomes
crucial for Gore, who is expected to lose much of the South and
West to Bush and running mate Dick Cheney of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore can't win this election without winning in New
England,'' said Joseph R. Paolino Jr., the former Providence mayor
and Gore's Rhode Island campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Paolino and other New England Democrats celebrated Gore's choice
of running mate and said the ''Lieberman effect'' should increase
turnout throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''More importantly, (Lieberman) will be a great vice president
of the United States,'' said New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, who
herself was on Gore's ''short list'' of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Secretary of the State Susan Bysiewicz said
Lieberman's presence ''adds interest'' for voters in Connecticut
and elsewhere. She noted that Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, grew up
in Gardner, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Clinton win all six New England states in 1992 and
1996, five of the six went for Bush rival John McCain in the
Republican primaries this year. Analysts said Gore and Lieberman
should expect another sweep this fall.
</P>
<P>
   That sweep might have happened anyway, but having Lieberman on
the ticket solidifies the region for Gore, said Darrell West, a
Brown University political science professor.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six New England states, Gore faced the biggest challenge
in Connecticut, where Bush was born and his father and grandfather
achieved great political success, West and other analysts said.
Recent polls show Gore and Bush in a dead heat in the state.
</P>
<P>
   With Lieberman joining the Democratic ticket, ''Connecticut is
definitely going Democratic,'' West said, adding that he expects
Republicans to ''write off'' the state's eight electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see them spending a lot of personal time or
advertising money in New England,'' West said. ''It's really not an
area that's likely to be good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Connecticut coordinator, Jay Malcynsky, insisted that the
Nutmeg State remains ''a battleground state.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Lieberman's addition to the ticket will cause GOP
donors to step up their efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Gray, a political adviser to Massachusetts Gov. Paul
Cellucci, said Republicans in the Bay State were not conceding
anything, either.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to run hard here, recognizing that it's a very
steep uphill climb,'' Gray said. Massachusetts was Clinton's
strongest state in 1996; he defeated Bob Dole by 33 percentage
points in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The race has not changed here because Al Gore put Joe
Lieberman on the ticket, and I don't expect that it will,'' Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Gov. John G. Rowland, Bush's top supporter in the
state, conceded that Lieberman's selection ''certainly makes it
more it difficult'' for Republicans to win Connecticut and the
region, but said that it does not guarantee a Democratic victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still believe no one votes for vice president,'' Rowland
said. ''People vote for the top of the ticket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-14-00 1702 </TRAILER>
