<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut deregulation aimed to prevent problems seen in California </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   When electric bills doubled in parts of California, the tidal
wave of outrage that swept up everyone from business owners to
surfer dudes rippled all the way to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut energy officials are monitoring the California
situation to see what lessons can be learned from the Golden State,
where tight supplies and summertime demand has led to a huge
increase in rates for some customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut law includes many strong consumer protections
and the construction of new power plants should help Connecticut
avoid California's headaches, power industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're turning an industry inside out and upside down with
these competitive forces, and the legislature's and DPUC's wisdom
is to shield customers from the impacts of that in the early stages
so you can allow the system to shake out,'' said Jim Sinclair,
spokesman for ISO New England, which manages the region's power
system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, consumer advocates said they would remain vigilant to any
price spikes or profiteering that may signal illegal behavior in
the newly emerging free market for power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until you have effective competition, there have to be relief
persons to detect these types of things, and you have to have rules
that allow you to protect customers,'' said Gene Koss, assistant
consumer counsel for Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut consumers are protected from price spikes until the
end of 2003 under the deregulation law passed two years ago. The
law mandates prices that are 10 percent under the prices set in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   After these price protections expire, however, the free market
will determine what happens. And no one knows for sure what that
will be.
</P>
<P>
   The economics chestnut of supply and demand dictates that prices
will go up if supply is tight and demand increases.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is in full display in the San Diego area. The
resulting chaos has driven some California lawmakers to demand an
end the state's experiment with deregulation while others have
proposed temporary help for besieged consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut lawmakers also have the option of extending price
controls or otherwise modifying the deregulation law if it appears
the market is not well developed by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike California, however, work is well underway to get more
power plants online in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Siting Council has approved plans for new power
plants that would add 3,162 megawatts to the current in-state power
supply of about 6,300 megawatts. A megawatt, or one million watts,
is enough power to supply about 300 homes.
</P>
<P>
   These new plants could replace old, inefficient and polluting
power plants now in operation and still generate more power to help
ease demand crunches, said Joel Rinebold, executive director of the
siting council.
</P>
<P>
   The council would like to see even more plants come into
Connecticut, but a power plant application is not a done deal,
Rinebold said. The council has rejected plans for plants in
Southington and New Milford.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have other protections in the new electric power
market. The law requires the Department of Public Utility Control,
the Office of Consumer Counsel and the state attorney general to
monitor power markets for anticompetitive practices.
</P>
<P>
   And public education efforts continue. Consumers are used to the
old, regulated system for electricity, where power prices remained
constant and were revised every few years.
</P>
<P>
   In the free market, where frantic deals are made on an hourly
basis, prices can go up, just as gasoline prices increase during
summer demand or fresh produce prices go up if crops are destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-14-00 1707 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000814.0094 </DOCNO>
