<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Binghamton man recipient of permanent artificial heart implant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - A 74-year-old Binghamton man has become
the first person in the United States to have a mechanical heart
permanently implanted in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial hearts are widely used to keep people on waiting
lists for transplants alive while waiting for a new human heart.
The procedure conducted on Robert De Santis at Sacred Heart Medical
Center in Spokane, Wash. is significant because the artificial
heart is meant to be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was part of an ongoing study at the hospital to
determine whether artificial hearts are a viable way to keep people
with end-stage heart disease alive.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent heart replacement operations already are common in
some parts of Europe, but have not received approval from the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
