<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infamous Extortionist Out of Jail  </HEADLINE>
By CORMAC WALSH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- After more than six years in jail, Germany's most
notorious extortionist was a free man Monday but that doesn't mean
he's done paying for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   He still owes the Karstadt department store chain $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Arno Funke, 50, was released from a Berlin prison shortly before
midnight Sunday -- a day ahead of schedule to avoid the expected
media swarm, a Berlin Justice Ministry spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of his nine-year sentence will be served as
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Funke, an electronics wizard, made a living by threatening to
set off bombs in German department stores unless they paid him
money. He bombed those that would not pay.
</P>
<P>
   The extortionist was arrested in April 1994 following a
department store bombing spree in Berlin that caused no injuries
but extensive damage to several stores.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were lucky, nobody was injured,'' said Michael Scheibe,
spokesman for the Karstadt group. ''But it could have been much
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Funke's first victim was the landmark KaDeWe store, which paid
him $230,000 in 1988 after he threatened to set off a bomb.
Authorities say he spent the entire amount, mainly on trips to
exotic locales.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he was back and calling himself ''Dagobert,''
the German name for Donald Duck's Uncle Scrooge. He chose that
moniker, he later explained, because he always ''wanted to swim in
money, just like Uncle Dagobert.''
</P>
<P>
   He demanded $650,000 from the Karstadt department store chain,
KaDeWe's parent company. After the chain refused to pay the money
he demanded, Funke set off several bombs in Karstadt stores,
causing about $2.3 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he grew in notoriety because of his unusual methods for
trying to collect and his ability to stay one step ahead of the
embarrassed police.
</P>
<P>
   His most ingenious plan was having police fill a device with
money and attach it to an Intercity train. Funke released the
device by radio for travel back to him on a single rail as he
waited at a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   He eluded capture at the last minute several times, once when a
detective in hot pursuit slipped on dog excrement and fell.
</P>
<P>
   He was finally arrested while making another ransom demand from
a Berlin telephone booth.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a book in prison about his exploits and has held a job
since 1998 as a cartoonist at a publishing house under a
work-release program. He plans to get married this year to a
43-year-old social worker.
</P>
<P>
   The two told the Bild am Sonntag newspaper they want to start a
new life. But Funke said he realized that would be difficult, given
that he stills owes Karstadt for the damage he caused.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm only earning $560 a month now and will be paying for my
deeds for the rest of my life,'' he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Scheibe said the Karstadt group intends to go after every penny
Funke makes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 1712 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
