<HEADLINE> Woman's foot is severed in fall from train  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - A woman's foot was severed when she
jumped from a freight train entering the United States from Canada,
U.S. Border Patrol officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who was not identified, was traveling with a
24-year-old Haitian, Joseph Roberto, when she jumped from the train
just inside the United States. Her foot was caught beneath the
wheels and was severed at the ankle, said Don Palacios, assistant
chief of the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   An American border agent had watched the train cross the
Whirlpool Rapids Bridge when he spotted the man and woman sitting
in a train car. The agent radioed the train engineer to stop and
chased the pair after they jumped from the train.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto was placed into custody pending charges of illegal entry
into the United States. He told authorities he had never met the
woman before the train ride, Palacios said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the woman, who was hospitalized in serious
condition after being flown by helicopter to the Erie County
Medical Center, would be interviewed later.
</P>
<P>
   Officials recovered the foot but doctors were unable to reattach
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
