<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With heavy rain, newly infected crows, Bergen County boosts bug spraying </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Health workers in Bergen County this week
will step up efforts to prevent transmission of the West Nile Virus
after eight more dead crows last week were found to be infected
with the mosquito-borne illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are now in peak mosquito breeding season, and the recent
heavy rains and warm weather have contributed to creating ideal
breeding habitat for mosquitoes,'' Bergen County Executive William
Pat Schuber said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Wednesday, the county health department will expand its
mosquito-control program to include ground-based spraying for adult
mosquitoes, said Thom Ammirato, Schuber's spokesman. Until now,
most of the county's spraying has been aimed at larvae to prevent
them from developing into mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying will be done between 3 a.m. and 6 a.m. to limit contact
by people and pets with the adult insecticide, then repeated about
four days later, weather permitting. Workers will be using
''Scourge,'' a synthetic version of an ingredient in the
chrysanthemum flower that is among the least toxic products
targeting adult mosquitoes. It degrades in less than four hours in
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea here is to hit the adult mosquitoes and kill them,''
Ammirato said, to limit human contact with the Culex mosquito,
which picks up the virus by feeding on an infected bird and then
can pass it on by biting people or other birds.
</P>
<P>
   He said workers initially will target neighborhoods in 38 Bergen
County towns within a mile of areas where infected crows have been
discovered. Most of the spraying will be done from the back of
trucks, although all-terrain vehicles and hand-held sprayers will
be used in wooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the infected birds initially were discovered in the
north central part of Bergen County, but now some have been found
in southern and western sections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like it's starting to spread a little bit,'' Ammirato
said.
</P>
<P>
   No New Jersey residents have been infected with the virus this
year. Blood or spinal fluid samples from 34 residents have been
tested for the virus, which is native to the Middle East and was
first identified in this country last September. Last summer, it
infected 62 people in New York State, killing seven of them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 89 dead crows found in northern and central New
Jersey have been confirmed by testing to be infected with the West
Nile Virus, according to the state Department of Health and Senior
Services. Of those, nearly half - 37 - were found in Bergen County.
</P>
<P>
   Another 19 were found in Middlesex County, along with 10 in
Passaic County, nine each in Union and Hudson counties, three in
Essex County and two in Monmouth County. In addition, a cockatiel
found in Monmouth County after apparently escaping from its owner
died from the virus July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The health department said 608 blood samples taken from
''sentinel'' chicken flocks in each of the state's 21 counties and
525 mosquito pools collected across the state all have tested
negative for the virus, which causes a high fever and flu-like
symptoms. Generally, it is only dangerous to the elderly, young
children and people with weak immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, health officials have been urging the public to try to
prevent contact with mosquitoes by eliminating any standing water
on their property, staying indoors when mosquitoes are most active
in the early morning and around dusk, and using insect repellent
and wearing long pants and long-sleeved shirts while outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State health department site on West Nile Virus:
http://www.state.nj.us/health/cd/westnile/enceph.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
