<HEADLINE> Terrorism suspect makes initial court appearance in United States  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - An Algerian accused of conspiring to support an
alleged bombing plot in the United States pleaded innocent as he
made his first appearance Monday in a U.S. court.
</P>
<P>
   Mokhtar Haouari, 31, entered the plea before U.S. District Judge
John F. Keenan. His U.S. lawyer, Daniel J. Ollen, said he had only
spoken to him for several minutes and could not yet discuss the
case.
</P>
<P>
   When he waived extradition in Canada last month, Haouari had
said through his lawyer there that he did not believe there was
evidence to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari was charged earlier this year in an indictment with
conspiring to provide and conceal material support to terrorists,
charges that upon conviction could result in a maximum prison term
of 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari is accused of joining with another Algerian, Abdel Ghani
Meskini, to help a third Algerian, Ahmed Ressam, who was arrested
in December as he crossed the border from Canada into Washington in
a car packed with bomb-making equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities have said Ressam was involved in plans to bomb
millennium celebrations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meskini was arrested in New York City soon after Ressam on
charges of providing support to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari has said he knew Ressam and Meskini but denied any
involvement in a terrorist plot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
