<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 148; Nasdaq Adds 60  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Monday, as cautious investors bet
positive economic news and stable interest rates will provide a
boost to second half profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 148.34 at 11,176.14.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 19.72 at 1,491.56, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 60.22 at 3,849.69.
</P>
<P>
   Investors turned bullish on blue-chip stocks last week, and that
sentiment extended into Monday's session. The catalyst was
encouraging inflation data, including a Labor Department report
that showed that wholesale prices remained virtually the same in
July after a huge jump in June caused by soaring energy costs. The
Dow index closed above 11,000 Friday for the first time since April
25.
</P>
<P>
   If economic indicators show inflation has been kept at bay, the
Fed will be less likely to raise interest rates at their next
meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Dow index jumped Monday after investors
turned to interest rate-sensitive retail stocks. Home Depot shares
rose $2.375 to $58.313, and Wal-Mart Stores was up 93.75 cents at
$52.50.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor shares also surged after an analyst said chip
prices should rise as demand increases later in the year. Micron
Technology rose $4.75 to $80.50, and Advanced Micro Devices rose
$6.25 to $63.25.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have kept pressure on technology stocks, however, in
the wake of warnings from some widely held companies that earnings
could fall in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting dynamics of benign inflation data pitted against
profit warnings have left investors with no clear motivation to
either buy or sell stocks. The result has been that the markets
have essentially fluctuated from day to day without breaking out in
any one direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is in the midst of tentative trading. On balance,
this is a market attempting to find a footing,'' said Alan
Ackerman, chief investment strategist Fahnestock Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're basically on hold until the Federal Reserve Board
meeting on Aug. 22,'' he added. ''Investors are watching and
waiting. We need to work our way through the uncertainty of what
the Fed will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet and telecommunications parts makers led the Nasdaq.
Juniper Networks gained $10.062 to $170, and Ciena Corp. was up
$7.563 to $163.688.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 948.36 million
shares, down from Friday's pace of 993.81 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 4.22 at 514.48.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.23 percent.
Germany's DAX index was up 0.12 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
0.55 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
