<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State college plans to issue tuition rebates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POMONA, N.J. (AP) - A college that reaped an unexpected $1
million windfall after sending out its tuition bills now plans to
offer rebates to students, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Richard Stockton College of New Jersey, a four-year state
liberal arts college, had planned a 9.8 percent tuition hike for
the academic year 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
   But the college's president, Vera King Farris, successfully
lobbied lawmakers for an increase in state aid because of
increasing enrollment. The state agreed to a one-time supplemental
allocation of $1 million to make up for the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   Because the grant came after tuition bills for the fall semester
had already been paid, Stockton plans to mail red-and-green tuition
rebate coupons to all 6,300 students for use in the spring
semester, Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   The college's board of trustees will vote on the rebate plan
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition, which cost $103 per credit last year and was to climb
to $112 in the fall, will instead cost $110, or 7.8 percent more
than the 1999-2000 academic year.
</P>
<P>
   The coupons, which will be good for rebates of $2 per credit,
will cut full-time students' bills by about $32 per semester.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rebates would cost the college about $165,000,
Farris said. The rest of the $1 million allocation will go to new
faculty jobs ($500,000), technology enhancements ($235,000) and
student scholarships ($100,000), Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was important to keep tuition costs low because most
Stockton students work in jobs for 25 to 30 hours a week and an
increase would have forced them to work even more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to keep faith. We've always had the lowest
tuition of the state schools and we would have (in 2000-2001)
anyway, but it was important to us to go even further,'' Farris
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
