<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GE looking for 100 people  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - After nearly a decade of downsizing,
General Electric is looking to hire blue-collar workers for its
Schenectady Power Systems plant.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants lined up outside the local Ramada Inn beginning at
8:30 a.m. Monday, hours before application acceptance began at 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, the state unemployment department processing
the applications had taken some 500 applicants for machinist and
assembly jobs offering between $12 and $20 hourly in addition to
full company benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they expected to field more than 2000
applications for the 200 available positions.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric's employment at its Schenectady birthplace has
fallen to less than 4,000 from the high of nearly 43,000 workers
during World War II. The job losses have cut property tax revenues,
hurt residential property values and fueled an exodus of people
from the city. In 1950, 96,000 people lived in Schenectady. Today,
about 65,000 remain.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems is now benefiting from a rush to increase
energy capacity, especially as recently deregulated utility
companies and independent power producers bet on hotter summers and
ever-increasing customer demand, spokeswoman Jan Smith said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Schenectady operation produces key components for building
gas-fired energy plants, considered more environmentally sound than
existing fossil fuel plants.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also investing $250 million at its Schenectady
site over the next three years for improvements ranging from
grounds maintenance to e-Business.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the company exhausted its list of workers laid off
within the last five years before issuing the call for more
workers.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric stock closed at $57.125, up 56 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
