<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With: BC-NJ--Flash Floods  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman asked the Clinton
administration Monday to declare Morris and Sussex counties
disaster areas so residents can begin to receive federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Whitman ordered both counties under a state
of emergency, giving the State Police superintendent power to order
evacuations, reroute traffic and open shelters. Whitman's order
also allows the state to activate New Jersey National Guard units.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of state and federal emergency personnel were still
assessing the damage done by Saturday's torrential rain. A
spokesman for Whitman put the price tag at over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Floods did more than $7.2 million in damage to public buildings
and that allows the state to request federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ''As governor, my main concern is to protect the health, safety
and welfare of our residents, and it's why I issued the executive
order,'' Whitman said in a statement issued Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the rain keeps falling, we already have an emergency
situation that needs to be addressed and can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   This formal request allows residents to start taking advantage
of federal aid programs, spokeswoman Jayne O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It puts in motion all of the federal flood relief programs,''
O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman asked federal officials to begin the process by
preparing estimates of the damage caused by the torrential
rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman ordered all state reports on damage from the flash
floods in by Monday morning so New Jersey officials could assess
what needs to be done and where the money would come from to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still in the process of getting those preliminary
numbers,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have precise standards for when damage
levels warrant disaster relief, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Federal Emergency Management Agency, Whitman
asked for the federal government to begin its formal assessment of
damage to property in the affected area.
</P>
<P>
   Early estimates at a Monday staff meeting put the costs at ''at
least $100 million,'' Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   But as officials met, that estimate kept changing, he said. With
each new assessment of the area more damage is found, McDonough
said.
</P>
<P>
   State money is likely not available for immediate relief since
the Whitman administration is still paying costs associated with
Tropical Storm Floyd last September, Whitman said. If aid comes, it
would have to come from the federal government, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With roads flooded, bridges washed out and dams burst, much of
the funding for immediate repairs would have to come from the
federal government, most likely the Department of Transportation,
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from the New Jersey Department of Transportation and the
Department of Environmental Protection are still in flood-damaged
areas and will remain there, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been there since Saturday night, and we will continue to
be there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They are joined by FEMA workers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's significant damage,'' said Whitman, who toured the
area by air Sunday. Homes have shifted from foundations, and
business have been washed out, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many houses in Warren and Sussex counties remained under water,
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you see 14 inches of rain in any finite period, there is
no natural waterway that can handle that kind of increase,''
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are hoping to have some assessment of the damage
and cost to repair available Monday, McDonough said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-14-00 1930 </TRAILER>
