<HEADLINE> New Venezuelan Congress Opens  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA OLSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's newly elected Congress
opened Monday, ending eight months of constitutional limbo that had
left power almost entirely in President Hugo Chavez's hands.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts about the 165-member Congress' ability to provide a
balance against the powerful presidency arose in its first session.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition legislators took the floor to condemn Chavez's
political coalition for selecting Congress's president, vice
president and second vice president behind closed doors. Chavez's
political party met with two other factions over a barbecue at the
presidential palace one week before the legislature opened to
choose the congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see how decisions are made here. They are made over a
barbecue in the president's house. And that is unfortunate,'' said
opposition legislator Julio Borges.
</P>
<P>
   A former coup leader popular with the country's poor, Chavez has
governed unopposed since January when a pro-government constituent
assembly closed the legislature after rewriting the constitution.
Chavez says he is dismantling a corrupt political regime he blames
for plunging the oil-rich nation of 24 million deeper into poverty.
Critics say he is compromising South America's longest-standing
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The new constitution demands that legislators vote according to
conscience rather than according to party discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chavez' allies hold a simple majority in Congress, they
lack the two-thirds needed to pass the 2001 budget and appoint the
Supreme Court magistrates and attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   A handpicked, 21-member provisional legislature, which included
Chavez's own brother, took over lawmaking duties until Venezuelans
elected the new Congress on July 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 1938 </TRAILER>
