<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christie Brinkley works the Democratic convention as a delegate  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Her image has appeared on countless magazine
covers, but Christie Brinkley wants to blend in as just another
face in the crowd at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thrilled to have the opportunity to hopefully sway a few
votes our way,'' said the former Sports Illustrated swimsuit model
who is one of New York's 294 delegates. ''I'll be just one of the
crowd down there waving my sign and wearing my 'smoosh Bush
button!'''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley has helped Bill Clinton and Al Gore raise money for
years. Gore returned the favor by seeing that Brinkley was made a
delegate.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived at the state's first delegation meeting Monday
toting a video camera to capture snippets of the convention for
Good Morning America.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton was speaking to delegates, but in the
back of the ballroom all eyes were on Brinkley and admirers- many
of them men - clustered around hoping for a hello. Her blue
polka-dot shirt was already crowded with buttons.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, leader of the
state's delegation called Brinkley's presence a tribute to the
delegation's diversity
</P>
<P>
   ''We have members of the New York State legislature and we have
members of the general public who are unheard of, just citizens who
want to be involved in the process, and we have Christie
Brinkley,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley, now 46, says she became politically active as a
teen-ager, protesting the Vietnam War and handing out George
McGovern pamphlets. When her career as a model took off, she became
a generous Democratic contributor.
</P>
<P>
   But the mother of three found a calling when she learned about
radioactive leaks at the Shoreham and Brookhaven nuclear reactors
near her home on the eastern tip of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Horrified, she was set to pick up and move her family until
actor and fellow Long Island resident Alec Baldwin reminded her
there was really nowhere to go to escape the nuclear problem
completely. She stayed and fought.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley is widely credited with helping persuade Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson to shut down the flux beam reactor at
Brookhaven. He made the announcement just a few weeks after meeting
with the former cover girl and other members of Standing for Truth
Against Radiation, the activist group she joined.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley says she knows many people dismiss her as just a pretty
face but that doesn't bother her in the slightest.
</P>
<P>
   ''A model talking about a nuclear power plant is going to
capture a different audience then a nuclear scientist will,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nukes are her pet issue but she's got a healthy backup list -
guns, abortion and Kosovo among them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, once Brinkley starts talking politics she's tough to
stop. Just bring up the recent Republican National Convention and
she's off and running, mimicking George W. Bush's Southern accent
and mocking the show the GOP made of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, it was such pandering. It was like 'read my lip service.'
It was like 'let's bring out George W.'s cutesy Latino nephew to
show how inclusive we are,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley, who has made a career in the world of glamour and good
looks, urged voters to look past the superficial come November.
</P>
<P>
   ''The media focus for so long has been on who's the better
dancer, who's got the cuter smile, who's the most charming,'' she
said. ''My message is ... don't get won over by the pandering and
the glossy showbizzy presentation. Look at everybody's voting
record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
