<HEADLINE> Lazio goes to Planet Hollywood, criticizes Clinton for raising soft money </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - With Hillary Clinton in Hollywood raising money
from celebrities and giving a prime time speech at the Democratic
National Convention, Rep. Rick Lazio made a campaign stop Monday at
... Planet Hollywood in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During the press conference at the financially troubled chain of
celebrity-themed eateries, the Republican Lazio pointed the finger
at Clinton for raising unregulated ''soft'' money in her campaign
against him for the U.S. Senate and for spending the weekend
prowling for donations among wealthy Democratic movie moguls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, my opponent Mrs. Clinton, is out on the West Coast,
raising millions of dollars out in Hollywood,'' said Lazio,
standing in front of a backdrop of cardboard cutouts of actors
including Bruce Willis and Arnold Schwarzenegger, who are major
investors in the eatery, as well as prominent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those dollars are soft dollars, unregulated, large amounts of
money that will come in and undermine campaign finance reform and
finance negative ads against me,'' said Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The event at Planet Hollywood, which filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection and closed nine of its 32 U.S. locations last
year, continued the candidates' elaborate dance around the use of
unregulated soft money.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the Long Island congressman have challenged
each other to forgo the use of such funds several times before -
but only if the other pledges to do so as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although each candidate says they are strong supporters of
campaign finance reform, they have not been able to reach
agreement. Clinton has raised about $1.2 million in soft money and
Lazio says he has not raised any. Third party organizations have
run television campaign commercials for both Clinton and Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as television cameras whirred and photographers
snapped, Lazio signed a ''freedom from soft money pact'' and then,
criticized Clinton for ''posturing politically.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''pact'' calls on the campaigns to refund soft money
contributions or donate the money to charity, and calls on the
candidates to discourage third party groups from running ads on
their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said his campaign would send the pact to Clinton ''out in
Hollywood'' for her to sign. Later Monday, Clinton campaign manager
Bill de Blasio released a copy of a letter sent to the Lazio camp,
offering an agreement -- with stipulations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pleased to hear that Mr. Lazio is now willing to
address the issue of campaign finance reform,'' de Blasio said.
''However, recent events give us reason to insist that any
agreement reached between our campaigns come with an ironclad,
verifiable method of accountability to ensure that it is honored
over the course of this race.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants Lazio to ''obtain letters of compliance from
the fourteen organizations currently engaging in independent
expenditure activity against Hillary Clinton, particularly in light
of his comments about not being able to personally control what
groups like the RLC do.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Lazio hammered Clinton for spending three days
out-of-state to raise money for her campaign, a reporter pointed
out that Lazio had just returned from a five-day, 14-city
out-of-state tour that raised more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily flummoxed, Lazio responded, ''this is different''
and said that the money he raised can only be used by his Senate
campaign committee, while Clinton's funds are being raised by one
of her soft money committees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-14-00 1944 </TRAILER>
