<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women celebrated $745 million verdict with thrift shopping  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A dozen women who recently won a $745 million
verdict against a former Bosnian Serb leader for atrocities
committed by his soldiers spent their last weekend in New York
buying clothing at thrift stores, a lawyer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They bought shoes and t-shirts for their families. We took
them to some thrift stores. Obviously, they didn't have much
money,'' said one of their lawyers, Maria T. Vullo.
</P>
<P>
   A jury returned its verdict Thursday after watching the women
tearfully recount their ordeals. But it was unclear if the women
will ever see a cent of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women were forced from their homes and subjected to
months of torture and rape in the early 1990s as Serbian soldiers
engaged in a campaign of ethnic cleansing, according to testimony
at a civil trial in federal court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The money is owed by former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic. Karadzic, an international fugitive, was previous
indicted by the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands,
on charges of genocide against other communities in the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The women were among 15 women and two survivor groups who sued
Karadzic under a 221-year-old U.S. law allowing foreign citizens to
sue foreign officials and citizens for violating the law of
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Vullo said the women had been in the United States for about
three weeks but had been too traumatized by the preparation for
their testimony to enjoy Manhattan until after the verdict. They
had, however, been taken to Little Italy for dinner one evening and
a few had visited museums.
</P>
<P>
   She said they celebrated the evening of the verdict by going to
a downtown jazz club. They spent the weekend visiting stores and
buying souvenirs and clothing for their families before leaving on
flights Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The verdict gave them some happiness,'' Vullo said. ''They
feel like they're going home with a victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
