<HEADLINE> Red Wings, Krupp Head to Arbitrator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Uwe Krupp and the Detroit Red Wings will meet
with an arbitrator Thursday in New York to determine if the club
owes the injured defenseman the $12.3 million left on his contract
</P>
<P>
   Krupp, who signed a guaranteed four-year, $16.4-million contract
before the 1998-99 season, injured his back shortly into his first
season with the Red Wings. Krupp hasn't played since, saying the
injury ended his career.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit suspended Krupp in August 1999 for failing to turn over
medical records of his back injuries. Krupp eventually released the
information, but remains suspended without pay because the Red
Wings found out Krupp was allegedly dogsledding while recovering
from a herniated disc.
</P>
<P>
   A decision in the case is not expected for weeks.
</P>
