<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pennsylvania company drilling for natural gas profits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) - Will the state's Southern Tier be the site
of the next natural gas boom?
</P>
<P>
   Several companies say they are expanding their drilling
operations in Chemung County, and at least one private couple has
struck gas on their land.
</P>
<P>
   Fairman Drilling Co. of DuBois, Pa. says it hopes to add up to
14 natural gas wells to the two it all already has.
</P>
<P>
   The company has leases for 16,000 to 20,000 acres in the
northwestern part of the county area and is looking to expand into
the towns' southern sections, said Roger Nelson, Fairman's project
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Fairman also is relying on seismic data to identify other areas
in Chemung County where successful gas wells can be drilled.
</P>
<P>
   Fairman isn't the only company probing the depths of Chemung
County in search of natural gas. Columbia Natural Resources, based
in Charleston, W.Va., operates a well in the town of Erin. Pacific
General Energies of Warren, Pa., operates another in Big Flats.
Potter McKean Resources, a smaller company based in Shinglehouse,
Pa., is operating in the town of Van Etten.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking for the shallower stuff at about 3,500 feet,''
said James Reynolds, a spokesman for Potter McKean. ''The deep
stuff just got hot in the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Fairman wells, at about 10,000 feet deep, are into the
''deep stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   One well is on land owned by Barney and Mary Broz in Veteran and
hit gas in March. The second, in Catlin on land owned by John
Whiteman, hit in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're elated. My wife and I figure we'll be able to do things.
We have a lot of nieces and nephews and can now help them,'' said
Barney Broz. ''They have no way knowing how much gas will be
produced, but they know it's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
