<HEADLINE> More mosquitos, birds found with West Nile in Suffolk County  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Eight more pools of mosquitoes and eight birds
were found infected with the West Nile virus in Suffolk County, the
county health commissioner announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The pools of mosquitos were collected in Belmont Lake State Park
between July 11 and July 25. The birds were collected between July
20 and July 27. Six of the birds were found in Babylon, and one
each in Brookhaven and Smithtown.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County has found infected mosquitos before.
</P>
<P>
   Only one person, a man from Staten Island who is recovering, has
been reported infected so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, seven people in the metropolitan area were killed as
the virus, which is transmitted from mosquitoes to humans, made its
first known appearance in the Western Hemisphere. Various testing
and mosquito-control measures have been taken since, including
regular collections of mosquitoes in traps to see where the
infection is present.
</P>
</TEXT>
