<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton Takes Center Stage  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Taking center stage as the first family's new
candidate, Hillary Rodham Clinton on Monday completed an odyssey
that has transformed her from a ''Goldwater girl'' of the 60s into
a darling of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In a to-die-for opportunity for a fledgling candidate, the first
lady was to deliver a prime-time address to the Democratic National
Convention just before President Clinton offered his political
farewell to the party's faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is only one choice in this election whether we're
talking about president, vice president or senator from New York
and the right choice is to keep going forward together,'' said the
U.S. Senate candidate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've made so much progress in the last eight years. We are a
stronger and better country than we were in 1992, but we have work
to do and we have challenges ahead,'' she told adoring delegates
from her adopted state as she tested out her speech hours before
taking the convention podium.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges include creating more jobs, improving education,
protecting the environment and providing ''quality affordable
health care to every New Yorker and every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats must ''stand up against any effort to turn back the
clock when it comes to gun safety measures'' and ''always protect a
woman's right to choose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she wanted ''to thank the American people for the
extraordinary eight years that my husband, my daughter and I have
enjoyed. It's been an experience and privilege of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's starring role was in sharp contrast to the role
her Republican opponent played at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia two weeks ago. Rick Lazio, a little-known congressman
from Long Island, stopped at his party's convention for only one
day and didn't speak before the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   For the first lady, her four-day visit to Los Angeles was a
nonstop celebrity affair. She appeared on ''The Tonight Show'' with
Jay Leno on Friday and picked up $1 million for her campaign at a
star-studded Hollywood tribute to her husband on Saturday night.
Before her convention speech Monday, she had interviews with the
three major television networks.
</P>
<P>
   In one pre-convention interview, CNN's Larry King asked the
first lady how she was doing emotionally in the wake of her
husband's affair with Monica Lewinsky. As she has in the past,
Clinton refused to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know that's my business, and I don't talk about my
personal business and I feel strongly that what goes on in a
marriage or a family should remain in that marriage and in that
family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During a surprise visit Monday to the Gay and Lesbian Caucus,
Clinton warned that Republicans ''have a very different vision of
America than we do.'' She said marching in New York City's gay
pride parade, with its flamboyantly attired marchers, was ''one of
the greatest thrills of my life ... I've never seen anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in a Republican household near Chicago, her
transformation into a Democrat began when she headed off to
Wellesley College. At Yale law School, she met her future husband
and began her lifelong work as an advocate for children.
</P>
<P>
   Republican critics have long maintained that her Senate run is
really meant to be a stepping stone to one day becoming the
nation's first female president.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton denies any such ambition, her supporters are
intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are the kind of guy we'd gladly accept as our first, first
guy,'' actress Alfre Woodard told the president during the
Hollywood tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York, which Clinton has called home only since
January, independent polls show her in a tight race with Lazio, who
announced his candidacy in May after New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani withdrew due to prostate cancer and marital problems.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's own well-publicized marital problems are
considered one reason she trails Lazio in the polls among white
women, a critical voting block in New York. She also trails among
male voters and is running below the 60 percent level among Jewish
voters that analysts believe she needs to win. She has already
asked vice presidential candidate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the first
Jew to be chosen for a major party ticket, to campaign for her in
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
