<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley says he'll help Gore, sees 'private sector' ahead  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Democrat Bill Bradley promised Monday to
actively campaign for Al Gore's presidential campaign and scoffed
at any suggestion that a Gore loss would boost his own prospects
for another White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of my efforts and thoughts are directed toward November,
not beyond that. I actually think I'll be moving toward the private
sector,'' Bradley said in an interview with The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before releasing his 359 delegates to vote for Gore, and a
day before addressing the Democratic National Convention, Bradley
said he deserved some credit for a primary challenge that made Gore
sharpen his message to emphasize issues like child poverty, health
care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Though qualified in his praise for Gore's style - he said the
vice president connects with people on a personal level ''from time
to time'' - Bradley said his own supporters should have little
problem choosing between the vice president and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look down the list of things that need to be done in the
country at a time when we have the means to do it, and you say
who's going to address these issues - whether it's health care or
poverty or education or working families. I don't think there's
much of a comparison,'' Bradley said. ''I think Al Gore is far and
away the better candidate for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not win a single state in his challenge to Gore. But
under Democratic Party rules, candidates winning at least 15
percent of the vote in any state receive delegates proportionate to
their showing.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley won about 420 delegates in all, but some were unpledged
''superdelegates'' who switched their support to Gore after Bradley
dropped out in March.
</P>
<P>
   By Bradley's count, he still had 359 delegates pledged to him.
On Monday, he asked them ''to make a commitment to Al Gore and to
the Democratic Party so we can win in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the AP interview Bradley was asked about his comments
during campaign that Gore did not tell the truth as a candidate and
thus might not be trustworthy as president.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he answered, ''I'm not going to rehash the primary.''
</P>
<P>
   The former three-term senator from New Jersey is keeping a
limited public schedule during the convention. He is to address
breakfast meetings of only two state delegations - New Jersey and
North Carolina. His prime-time address is Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has lost the 15 pounds he gained on the campaign
trail, plus five more.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of my own life,'' Bradley said, ''I'm following the
advice that Tom Dewey gave Richard Nixon in 1960 when he wrote him
a letter saying, 'If you lose the presidential race don't make any
life decisions for six months.' I think it's very good advice.''
</P>
<P>
   He has spent part of the past five months writing a book based
on the speeches and ideas that were central to his campaign. The
book, ''The Journey From Here,'' will reach bookstores in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wrote it,'' he said, ''to answer the question somebody might
have, 'So what was that Bradley campaign about in 2000?'''
</P>
<P>
   He will spend some time on a book tour this fall but denied that
will be a diversion from his efforts to help Gore and Democratic
congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be actively out campaigning for the ticket and
for Democrats around the country,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his background makes him strong in battleground states
like Missouri, where he grew up, and New Jersey, where he served in
the Senate, as well as Pennsylvania and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think all those are areas where I could be helpful, and I'm
willing to,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
