<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union Leaders: Nader Can Hurt Gore  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two major union leaders sent a pointed
message Monday to third party candidate Ralph Nader: You can only
hurt Al Gore and labor causes.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James Hoffa said his union had ruled out
endorsing Nader despite the Green Party candidate's decision to
join the union in opposing permanent normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have to look at reality as to who has a chance of
winning,'' Hoffa said in an interview with The Associated Press.
''And while I have great respect for him, I think it's going to be
hard for him to pull enough votes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney agreed, saying Nader will only
siphon votes away from Gore, whom most major unions are backing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is one of two major candidates will be elected
president,'' he said. ''We are going to be out there working with
the rank-and-file members who are leaning in some cases toward
Nader to educate them on the issues and to remind them of what the
reality of the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader fired back, accusing the union leaders of taking the
position that as long as Republicans are considered worse, they
will support the Democrats no matter what their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has to be a new start and if we cannot receive the labor
leaders' support, we will continue to defend and receive the
support of the rank and file,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a separate AP interview, Sweeney said Gore's record on
labor issues, outside of his position on free trade, was very
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, Al Gore's record and his position on major issues
is as close as you can get to our position,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO noted that both Gore and his running mate,
Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, supported the labor federation's
positions more than 80 percent of the time, while Republican
vice-presidential nominee Dick Cheney had a 6 percent favorable
voting record while serving in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said that union leaders would tell their members about
Gore's pro-labor record and about Nader's inability to win. In
addition, he said Nader until recently could not be found on a
picket line or lending his support to a union's effort to negotiate
a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   While the Teamsters have yet to endorse a presidential
candidate, Hoffa said the Democrats can't win without the support
of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ''They should be very careful to tailor their message to make
sure they get the support of working families and union families,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader said that every vote he receives would enhance
organized labor's clout in the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever millions of votes I get will send a message to the
Democrats that they cannot continue to take labor and labor unions
for granted,'' Nader said. ''It's difficult to discern how many
more betrayals and lies by the Democratic Party it will take before
organized labor decides to help build a new progressive, pro-worker
political movement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
