<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealander May Steer U.S. Boat  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New Zealander may steer the next American boat to win the
America's Cup, a source of patriotic pride during 132 years of U.S.
domination. Now it's a prize sought by billionaires wooing sailors
more concerned with cash than citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dickson, who drove New Zealand's first America's Cup entry
in 1987 to a 37-1 record before losing in the semifinals, is a top
prospect for skipper of the team being assembled by Larry Ellison,
chief executive officer of software giant Oracle, for the 2002-2003
Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''He certainly is a likely candidate,'' Bill Erkelens, chief
operating officer of Oracle Racing Inc., said Monday. Dickson, part
of Ellison's maxiboat team for several years, would be sailing for
his third country in four America's Cup campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   No skipper has won the Cup for a country other than his own.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand replaced the United States as the America's Cup
power when it won in 1995 off San Diego against an American boat
skippered by Paul Cayard. It successfully defended it this year
against Prada of Italy, which eliminated Cayard's AmericaOne in the
semifinals off Auckland, where the next competition will be held.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cayard announced he sold two boats and other
AmericaOne assets to Ellison, citing the growing cost of putting
together a strong team. With four billionaires expected to compete,
Cayard said the $30 million he could reasonably raise was less than
half what his opponents, including Ellison, could come up with.
</P>
<P>
   One billionaire, Ernesto Bertarelli of Switzerland, lured away
Russell Coutts and Brad Butterworth, the skipper and tactician for
New Zealand's two winning efforts. Two other Team New Zealand crew
members are with Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dickson has a long relationship with Larry as a skipper, so
he's the incumbent skipper,'' said Cayard, Oracle's campaign
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be a part of the sailing team,'' Cayard added during a
conference call with Erkelens. ''I don't think any of that is
sorted out yet as to what my role will be.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be skipper. Dickson was skipper of Ellison's
boat, Sayonara, which won the Sydney-to-Hobart race in 1998 in
which six sailors died in winds up to 90 mph and swells reaching 35
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''When (Ellison) found out some of these (Sayonara crew members)
were considering moving along, he decided that it might be time to
jump into the game,'' Erkelens said of Ellison's Cup interest.
''Larry would like to be involved as much as his schedule allows''
but it appeared unlikely he would be a regular crew member.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson was 24 during the 1986-87 Cup competition and one of New
Zealand's bright hopes. But in 1992, he was the skipper of Japan's
first Cup campaign and, in 1995, he drove Tag Heuer, one of two
Kiwi boats in the competition. The other one, raced by Team New
Zealand, won the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The United States won all 25 Cups from 1851 through 1980.
Australia II beat Dennis Conner's Liberty in 1983, but Conner
regained the Cup in Fremantle, Australia, four years later. He
successfully defended it in 1988, and the United States kept it in
1992 when America3 beat Il Moro di Venezia of Italy, skippered by
Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said Ellison's effort would represent the St. Francis
Yacht Club in San Francisco, just as AmericaOne did.
</P>
<P>
   Erkelens said Oracle would begin sailing one of the AmericaOne
boats off Auckland in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 2127 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000814.0148 </DOCNO>
