<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kristin Gore Moves Into Spotlight  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore's daughter Karenna likes to say how
many doors she's knocked on urging people to vote for her dad.
Yeah, it means ''lots of restraining orders'' chimes in sister
Kristin.
</P>
<P>
   Bada-boom. Kristin Gore's a comedy writer who still hasn't quite
gotten used to the spotlight cast by her would-be president dad.
But there's nothing like jumping in with both feet: She and
big-sister Karenna hammed it up with Jay Leno on ''The Tonight
Show'' Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No, their dad's not stiff, the sisters insisted -- they don't
know what perpetuates that image.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kristin writes jokes for her dad, ''about him,
sometimes,'' she confessed to Leno. ''I try to keep him in a good
mood generally.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-something crowd obviously thinks this Gore daughter is
funny -- the Fox TV show she has written for since May, Futurama, is
considered the epitome of hip.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't get much chance to showcase that humor with Leno,
though -- another comedian, Jon Stewart, stole the show with
wisecracks. But the sisters revealed a pretty human side of their
dad: When they were kids and wanted to swim, he'd sneak them in to
a congressional pool through the all-male gym. Yes, sometimes it
meant running into tubby senators wrapped in towels.
</P>
<P>
   ''They burst in on Ted Kennedy and he goes 'ah good you're
here,''' Stewart interjects as Schiff covered her face to smother
the grin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Monday's late-night TV gave major exposure to a Gore
daughter who's kind of shy, preferring to help her dad's campaign
behind the scenes. It also was a warmup for Thursday, when millions
will watch Kristin Gore on prime-time as she introduces mom Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Is all the attention overwhelming?
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh no, not at all,'' the 23-year-old deadpanned, surrounded by
about 50 reporters and TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the fun with stars like Leno, Kristin and her sister
are working the town with serious reasons to vote for their dad.
Until Al Gore and wife Tipper arrive Wednesday, the sisters are the
would-be president's chief ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff took to the convention podium Monday to unveil a new
interactive Internet site -- http://www.algore.com -- that lets Web
surfers e-mail questions to Gore and running mate Joe Lieberman,
register to vote online, or volunteer to help the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a live online chat with Democrats, Schiff called the Internet
important in rallying voters to Gore, and called this election
vital.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the next president will reshape the Supreme Court,
appointing several new justices. The selections are crucial for
such issues as women's choice in abortion, curbing gun violence and
safeguarding HMO patients, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will impact people's lives,'' said Schiff, calling
differences between the two political parties ''crystal clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, 27, is an old pro at this kind of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But Kristin Gore, a writer not an orator, is still feeling her
way.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping at a party for delegates from Oregon, Alaska and
Washington, Kristin declined an offer to address the crowd but
shook hands from the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was to see more than 500 young Democrats gathered for
a Goo Goo Dolls concert. Her message: ''We are the party of
workers' rights, and the party of the minimum wage.''
</P>
<P>
   One-on-one, however, Kristin Gore charms.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a delightful young woman,'' said Judith Mehrens of
Clackamus, Ore., who spoke with her at the delegation party. ''She
is very warm, very real. She told me, 'Thanks for being here.
Thanks for helping my dad.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
