<HEADLINE> Liberty 78, Mystics 57  </HEADLINE>
By MELISSA MURPHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Becky Hammon scored 19 points as the New York
Liberty defeated the Washington Mystics 78-57 Monday night and
advanced to the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Tari Phillips added 15 points and 10 rebounds for the Liberty in
Game 2 of the best-of-three conference playoffs. New York will face
Tuesday's winner of the Cleveland-Orlando series on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, selected the WNBA's most improved player on Monday,
finished 7-for-11 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Chamique Holdsclaw scored 12 points on 6-for-15 shooting for the
Mystics, who bowed out of the first playoff appearance in the
franchise's three-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Markita Aldridge also had 12 points while Nikki McCray, who
averaged 15.5 points, was held scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Johnson, Tamika Whitmore and Crystal Robinson scored 10
points apiece for the Liberty, who have won 11 straight home games.
New York's last home loss was a 72-67 setback on June 25 against
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty shot 52.5 percent from the field, including 6-for-12
from 3-point range. The Mystics were outscored 40-28 in the paint
and outrebounded 31-19.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead by 15 at halftime, New York extended the lead to 48-32 on
Phillips' third straight layup five minutes into the second half.
She left the game after getting an elbow in the mouth and chipping
her tooth with 11:53 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Wicks' 16-foot jumper gave the Liberty a 58-38 lead and
consecutive 3-pointers by Hammon and Robinson made it 64-42 with
8:03 left.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips sat out five minutes before adding a putback, and the
Mystics could get no closer than 68-50 the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   New York led 12-4 in the opening five minutes on Johnson's
baseline 3-point shot, which capped a 7-0 run. A tip-in by Wicks
extended the lead to 15 points before Vicky Bullett's two free
throws stopped a 9-0 Liberty run at 26-13 with 7:03 remaining in
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight layups by Holdsclaw, who scored eight points in
the opening period, trimmed the lead to 26-19 with 4:55 remaining.
But New York closed out the half on a 14-6 run -- behind six points
Whitmore -- for a 40-25 halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
