<HEADLINE> Celebrities Mix With Politicians  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former President Carter and an actor who
plays a president on TV, Martin Sheen, shared a lunch table Monday
near the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have two presidents here today -- President Carter and
acting President Bartlet,'' said Gov. Gray Davis, who hosted a
lunch for Democratic governors.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen plays President Josiah Bartlet on NBC's ''The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendees saw a montage of Hollywood depictions of politicians,
from ''Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'' to ''All the President's
Men'' and ''Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ''West Wing'' was not among the clips.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred donors and activists who have supported Davis'
re-election and the Democratic Governors Association nibbled on
chicken, potatoes and vegetables at the lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Call it dances with delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Costner opened up his home Monday to South Dakota's
delegation to the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The star of ''Dances With Wolves'' and ''For Love Of The Game''
shook hands and chatted with each member of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little too hard to believe, actually, being in a movie
star's home. How many people in South Dakota get to experience
this?'' said delegate Stana Donelly.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The day may belong to Al Gore, but the night belonged to his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff and her sister, Kristin, took the stage
Sunday night with the Goo Goo Dolls to honor young Democrats at
Hollywood's Knitting Factory nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were considering doing a couple of numbers, but I think
we're going to turn this over to the Goo Goo Dolls,'' said Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Gore's daughters brought high security to the
small club.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked one of those Secret Service dudes to frisk me, but
they weren't interested. I thought they should earn their money,''
said Goo Goo Dolls lead singer John Rzeznik.
</P>
<P>
   Decked out in red leather pants and a tank top, Rzeznik painted
an odd picture next to the Gore girls in dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Want to hear a joke?'' Rzeznik asked. ''How many Republicans
does it take to screw in a light bulb? None. They don't have a ...
clue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goo Goo Dolls played a four-song set, including their hit
''Broadway,'' which brought the Gore daughters to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Dylan McDermott, star of the hit TV show ''The Practice,'' gave
the convention's opening session a little bit of Hollywood gloss by
joining three children in reading portions of the Declaration of
Independence and telling a little about those who signed the
revolutionary document.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know who wrote the declaration and we think we know the
text,'' McDermott said. ''But most of us remember only two or three
phrases from it, and have little knowledge of how it came about,
what went into it, what happened to the 56 rebels who framed and
signed it.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott showed off an original copy of the declaration, issued
on July 4, 1776.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pursuit of happiness and the equality of opportunity
continues,'' McDermott said. ''It is on the agenda of this
convention. For every one of the 56 original signers of the
declaration, there are a million of us to whom it is sacred and
alive and immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott had the crowd all revved up for Melissa Ethridge, who
sang a medley of patriotic songs, including ''This Land is Your
Land.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Def Jam Records co-founder Russell Simmons, one of the artists
behind Rap the Vote 2000, says he wasn't always a responsible
individual.
</P>
<P>
   ''The actual responsibility that comes along with the position I
have, I have not always accepted,'' Simmons said Monday during a
convention panel discussion with Grammy Award-winning singer Erykah
Badu and John Singleton, director of ''Boyz in the Hood'' and this
summer's ''Shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simmons, who produced albums for Public Enemy and the
Beastie Boys, said he found his political voice when young people
played a part in electing President Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the rap community is not as socially conscious as
they were a few years ago,'' he said Monday during the Democracy
2000 forum at the convention. ''We've got to get back to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said the convention and the pending election are a
chance for young people to have a say.
</P>
<P>
   ''This whole thing is about having a voice, and we have to fight
for that voice,'' he said. ''Eight years ago, we got the old people
out of (the White House).''
</P>
<P>
   Badu said many young minority people feel left out of the
political process. The challenge, she said, is to get them
involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
