<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Health Minister Says Deal Is Nearer on Medicare Funding
<TEXT>
<P>
   SASKATOON, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Ottawa and the provinces are
closer than ever to reaching a deal on increased funding for
medicare, federal Health Minister Allan Rock told a doctors
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear there's now a real convergence in the approaches of
the federal, provincial and territorial governments,'' Rock said
days after the premiers met to try to reach a common front on
revitalizing health care.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money and how it's going to be paid out remains
the largest stumbling block to a deal, but Rock said both levels of
government have now identified some priorities. Those include the
supply of doctors and nurses, medical infrastructure, the use of
new drugs and health promotion and prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prime minister and I are confident that while there still
remains work to do, the basis has been laid for a successful first
ministers meeting,'' he said, referring to a follow-up meeting the
premiers will have with Jean Chretien in September.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's comments to the Canadian Medical Association follow a
move by the premiers on Friday to ask Ottawa to restore $4.2
billion in transfer payments cut more than five years ago during
Finance Minister Paul Martin's campaign to eliminate the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Health Officials: Latest E. coli Cases Aren't Cause for Alarm
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Three children from Walkerton, Ontario who tested
positive for E. coli late last month became sick with the deadly
bacteria in the spring but never went to hospital, health officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth child picked up an infection in late July, possibly
through exposure to livestock, said Dr. Walter Ewing, associate
medical officer of health with the Bruce-Grey-Owen Sound health
unit.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the cases are a sign the bacteria that has haunted
Walkerton since May is making a comeback, Ewing said as he tried to
quell mounting anger and fear in the town of 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no new cases associated with Walkerton -- they are
old cases that have been recently diagnosed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other patients who showed symptoms consistent with an E.
coli infection have tested negative for the bacteria, Waram said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, however, tested positive for camphyllobacter -- a
less virulent bacteria that leads to E.-coli-like symptoms, such as
telltale bloody diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Federal Bid To Ban Native Lobster Fishermen Is Rejected
</P>
<P>
   MIRAMICHI, New Brunswick (AP) -- The federal Fisheries Department
got no sympathy from the New Brunswick court system Monday as it
attempted to ban some natives from the waters of Miramichi Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Four aboriginal men charged with obstructing fisheries officers
during a weekend confrontation near the Burnt Church First Nation
were released from custody after fisheries officials lost their bid
to have them outlawed from the bay and its contentious lobster
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries officer Wayne Thompson described in provincial court
boat rammings and other incidents that have increased tensions in
the lobster dispute on Miramichi Bay in northeastern New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the case wanted Judge Denis Lordon to put special
constraints on the release of the four fishermen -- specifically
that they not be allowed near, or on, the bay.
</P>
<P>
   But Lordon dismissed the request, noting that the Burnt Church
First Nation, where the four men live, is located on the banks of
the large bay.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend seizure and destruction of almost 750 traps set by
natives led to ugly confrontations between natives and fisheries
officers on the water. It also resulted in retaliatory native
blockades on a major public highway that runs by the Burnt Church
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Woman Convicted of Exploiting Foster Daughter Can't Appeal
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- A woman convicted of sexually
exploiting the foster daughter who is now her live-in lesbian lover
will not escape a criminal record, the British Columbia Court of
Appeal ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel dismissed Valerie Hetu's request to appeal
her conditional sentence without even hearing from the Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Hetu, 32, was convicted in March of sexually exploiting Candice
Prince in 1998 when the girl was 16.
</P>
<P>
   She received a six-month conditional sentence and was ordered to
perform 100 hours of community service work.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Watt, Hetu's lawyer, was seeking a conditional
discharge, which would have meant Hetu would have no criminal
record as she does now.
</P>
<P>
   Hetu and Prince met at church in 1998 and Hetu approached the
Ministry of Children and Families for permission to become the
girl's foster parent.
</P>
<P>
   Prince, then a troubled 16-year-old, came to live with Hetu and
her family several months later.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after Prince moved in, Hetu's former husband, Doug
Hetu, testified he witnessed the pair kissing on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Prince remained in the home for four months while social workers
looked for another foster home, but there was no evidence of any
further sexual contact, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
