<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Packers Brooks Signs With Denver  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Saying he was eager to get started, wide
receiver Robert Brooks proved it, signing a one-year contract with
the Denver Broncos on Monday and immediately joining his new
teammates at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, the former Green Bay standout who retired last August
because of a back injury, said he chose Denver's offer over those
of three other NFL teams because ''I think this is a good
situation. These guys have a tradition for winning. That's what I'm
used to, and that's where I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' incentive-laden contract will pay him a reported
$750,000 that could go as high as $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, 30, had a favorable workout for the Broncos on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Confident he is recovered from the back injury that contributed
to his retirement, Brooks was adamant about signing a one-year deal
''so I can prove the skeptics wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 177-pound Brooks was one of the NFL's most prolific
receivers before his injury. His best year was 1995 when he caught
a career-best 102 passes for 1,497 yards and 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent back surgery in August 1998 to remove a herniated
disk, then had surgery again in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very healthy,'' said Brooks, who has been working out with
a personal trainer in his hometown of Phoenix for several months.
''I think it will show when I get out there on the practice field
and get an opportunity to play in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he thought it would take to learn the offense and
begin making a contribution, Brooks said, ''When does practice
start? Tomorrow? First of all, it's not a new system. They run the
same system that I ran for seven years, so that will be an easy
transition. And as far as playing football, I think if you are a
player, you never forget how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos coach Mike Shanahan agreed that Brooks' mental
transition should be seamless.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing that's good is he's used to the same terminology,''
Shanahan said. ''The system is very similar to what he went through
in Green Bay relative to X, Y and Zs (receiver positions). So I
think he's going to pick that up a lot quicker than most.
</P>
<P>
   ''How fast can he come in and get in football shape? I think
that will take some time, probably two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're happy to have him. This will give us a chance to see
what he can do after being laid off for a year. He came in here in
great shape, and we're hoping he can come and help our football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks won't immediately challenge for a starting job. He said
he was told frankly by Shanahan before he signed that Ed McCaffrey
and Rod Smith were the starters. The Broncos' backup positions are
in flux, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mike hasn't promised me anything, that's for sure,'' Brooks
said. ''I'm just coming in here trying to help this team win and do
whatever I can to contribute to the guys they already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks created the Lambeau Leap in Green Bay, jumping into the
stands after a touchdown. That will be more difficult at Mile High
Stadium, with its chain-link fence surrounding most of the field
and a high wall in the south end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to (Broncos defensive tackle) Keith Traylor and he
said that if I can help bring some magic to this team, then we are
going to see about getting the fences taken down or getting the
stands lowered or something,'' Brooks joked. ''And Traylor is a big
guy, so I think we can get some things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 2249 </TRAILER>
