<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Food Convoys Head to Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Two humanitarian convoys with desperately
needed food for Chechnya left neighboring Ingushetia on Monday, the
World Food Program said.
</P>
<P>
   The food delivery was announced as rebels mounted a wave of
attacks on Russian troops in the war-ravaged republic.
</P>
<P>
   The convoys are carrying supplies for 35,000 people facing
starvation in the Chechen capital, Grozny, and the border district
of Urus-Martin as a result of the long-running military conflict,
the World Food Program said.
</P>
<P>
   The Grozny convoy consists of 10 trucks carrying about 132 tons
of wheat flour, grain, and vegetable oil that will be distributed
to 31,000 people, WFP said. It will be distributed to elderly, ill
and handicapped Chechens along with single mothers and children who
were unable to flee the capital when fighting flared last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The second convoy of five trucks is carrying mixed food for more
than 3,500 displaced people from the village of Komsomolskoe in
Urus-Martan which was completely flattened during the flare-up in
fighting, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These civilian victims of the conflict in Chechnya are clearly
in a very dangerous situation, particularly the people in Grozny,''
Bhim Udas, WFP emergency coordinator for the northern Caucasus said
in a statement. ''They are the last in line for food access and we
are very anxious to get relief to them before they begin suffering
the effects of severe malnutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight Monday, rebel forces attacked Russian checkpoints 22
times, a major increase in activity after several days of quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Several Russian troops were wounded in the attacks, but it
wasn't known if any had died, officials said. Ten of the attacks
took place in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels periodically strike Russian checkpoints and military
columns, but such a high number of attacks in one night was
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, a powerful bomb went off about 10 yards
from an Emergency Situations Ministry installation in Grozny, but
there were no inuries, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Federal troops moved into Chechnya in September to end the
republic's de facto independence after a series of cross-border
raids by Islamic militants based in Chechnya and bombings in Russia
that Moscow blamed on the rebels last year. Russian troops withdrew
from Chechnya in defeat at the end of a 1994-96 war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 2250 </TRAILER>
