<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers Pull Glynn For More Tests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Texas pitcher Ryan Glynn, who fainted in
the dugout after being pulled out of his last game, was been
scratched from his scheduled start Wednesday to give team doctors
more time to evaluate his condition.
</P>
<P>
   Medical tests haven't determined why Glynn passed out in the
dugout after being taken out of Friday night's game. The Rangers
had originally said that Glynn would make his next start Wednesday
against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Hunter, the team's internist, said Glynn would be put
through a series of medical tests over the next 7-10 days. Under
that timetable, Glynn (2-3) could miss at least two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he had no new medical information, but felt
uncomfortable allowing Glynn to return to game action until the
tests could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to find the cause and make sure it doesn't repeat
itself,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn has no medical background that would explain the fainting.
After he threw 95 pitches Friday, when the game time temperature
was 98 degrees, speculation was that the pitcher may have suffered
from heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Heat may have provoked it, but I don't think it was the only
factor,'' Hunter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
