<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Addresses Democratic Party
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In an emotional last hurrah before the Democratic
Convention, President Clinton tonight asked voters to elect Vice President Al
Gore as his successor and to send first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to the U.S.
Senate from New York. Clinton told Democrats that he has delivered on the
promise of 1992, saying, ''I ran for president to change the future, for those
left behind in America.'' He recalled: ''I made one of the best decisions of my
life: asking Al Gore to be my partner.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Lady Speaks at Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton thanked Americans tonight ''for
your faith and support in good times -- and in bad,'' completing her
transformation from first lady to U.S. Senate candidate from New York. The first
lady made a prime-time address to the Democratic National Convention just before
President Clinton offered his political farewell to the party faithful. She
hailed his administration and called for voters to elect Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman to carry on that work.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hurricane Warnings Posted in Texas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- As big storm approached from the Gulf of Mexico,
hurricane warnings went up today along 230 miles of coastline in Texas and
Mexico. By tonight, Tropical Storm Beryl had sustained winds of 50 mph. It was
centered about 125 miles south-southwest of Brownsville. Beryl could reach
hurricane strength -- sustained winds of at least 75 mph -- before coming ashore
tomorrow near the U.S.-Mexico border, said the National Hurricane Center in
Miami.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians Trying To Rescue Sub
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian navy is trying to find a way to rescue more than
100 sailors trapped at the bottom of the Barents Sea in a crippled submarine. By
early Tuesday, about a dozen military ships including a nuclear-powered cruiser
were at the site, Russian reports said. The chance of a happy ending was ''not
very high,'' the navy chief conceded. The Kursk, one of Russia's biggest nuclear
submarines, was apparently involved in a collision before it plunged hundreds of
feet near the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Koreans Visit Families in South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A group of 100 separated family members from North
Korea arrived in South Korea Tuesday for temporary reunions with relatives they
have not seen for half a century. A passenger jet of Air Koryo, North Korea's
national airline, ferried the aging family members from Pyongyang on a 50-minute
flight to Seoul's Kimpo airport and prepared to pick up 100 South Koreans for
similar exchanges in the North.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Safety Experts: Widen Tire Recall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Safety advocates and attorneys suing Ford Motor Co. and
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. accused the companies today of dangerously limiting
the size of a Firestone tire recall, and urged them to broaden it. Company
officials said their actions were sufficient and that the overwhelmingly
majority of complaints were from the tires being recalled. Bridgestone/Firestone
said last week it would recall all of the P235/75R15 size radial ATX and ATX II
tires, and Wilderness AT tires of the same size made in Decatur, Ill. The 6.5
million 15-inch tires in question were mostly installed on Ford vehicles,
notably the Explorer SUV.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Social Security Turns 65
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WOODLAWN, Md. (AP) -- Social Security, the agency that provides a financial
safety net for millions of elderly and retired Americans, has reached the
milestone that most of its members await: its 65th birthday. About 300 past and
present Social Security Administration employees joined Commissioner Kenneth S.
Apfel today to dedicate a garden at the agency's Woodlawn headquarters. The
centerpiece is a bust of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, who signed the
Social Security Act on Aug. 14, 1935.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Soft Drink Biz Blasts Caffeine Study
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A study suggesting that caffeine is added to colas to hook
consumers was decried today by the soft drink industry, which called the results
flawed and irresponsible. The study's authors, from Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions, said about 70 percent of soft drinks sold nationwide contain
caffeine. Caffeine ''is added for one reason, for flavor,'' said Jeff Nedelman
of the National Soft Drink Association.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Edge Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index inched higher Tuesday in
thin trading. The Nikkei gained 1.31 points to 16,155.22 in the morning session.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average on Monday closed up 148.34 at
11,176.14 and the Nasdaq was up 60.22 at 3,849.69.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rams WR Isaac Bruce Has $40M Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Wide receiver Isaac Bruce today signed a six-year,
$40 million contract extension with the Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams. The
Rams announced the deal shortly before an exhibition with the Tennessee Titans,
the team they beat for the NFL title.
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER 
</P>
