<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More heavy rain in northwest N.J. brings more flooding and evacuations </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - Heavy rain drenched northwestern New
Jersey on Monday for the second time in three days, straining more
dams to the breaking point and forcing hundreds of additional
evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said she would ask the Clinton
administration to declare Morris and Sussex counties disaster
areas. She put both counties under a state of emergency, allowing
the state to order evacuations and activate New Jersey National
Guard units.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Warren County were also inundated.
</P>
<P>
   No serious injuries have been reported since Saturday's
downpour, whose torrents damaged dozens of homes, devoured Newton's
water supply system, and claimed bridges, roads and dams.
</P>
<P>
   The cost will surpass $100 million, Whitman spokesman Peter
McDonough said. Estimates were not complete Monday, since some
areas were still under water and could not be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   As serious as the damage was, it paled in comparison to the
ravages of Tropical Storm Floyd 11 months ago, which caused about
$1 billion in damage, much of it in the central New Jersey towns of
Bound Brook and Manville.
</P>
<P>
   In Sussex County, an additional 100 homes were evacuated Monday
in Sparta and 150 homes in Byram, while some residents in
Ogdensburg were also urged to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're up to our tail in alligators right now,'' Sussex County
emergency coordinator Eskil ''Skip'' Danielson said.
</P>
<P>
   Danielson said Monday night there were still serious water
problems in Byram and Stanhope and that damage assessment would
continue Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got so much work to do,'' Danielson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Warren County to the south, Hackettstown Mayor Roger Hines
advised 300 families in low-lying areas to leave their homes, amid
concern that upstream dams could burst. About a dozen people were
evacuated in Hackettstown Monday, according to Gary Wassel, deputy
coordinator of emergency management in Warren County. Wassel said a
downpour Monday night did not cause additional problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're watching carefully,'' Wassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Raymond Rafferty said the hour-long downpour Monday night
seemed to have little effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''It didn't add to our mess,'' Rafferty said.
</P>
<P>
   The Musconetcong River, which flows out of Sussex County and
borders Morris and Warren counties, rose a foot an hour Monday
before cresting in mid-afternoon, said Red Cross spokeswoman Cathy
Derechailo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The river is expected to maintain its crest peak for two to
three days. So this is far from over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency expected evacuations in downriver areas such as
Allamuchy and Byram would bring up to 200 people to its emergency
shelter at Hackettstown High School, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The school was reopened for shelter Monday, after the Red Cross
closed all six shelters that had opened Saturday afternoon amid the
downpour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state is investigating claims that 14 inches of
rain fell Saturday in Sparta when a storm system stalled over the
hilly region.
</P>
<P>
   A better estimate is 8 to 10 inches, said David Robinson, state
climatologist at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   ''That 14 inches is probably high and we've traced that back to
the gauge that gave us that figure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intermittent showers and thunderstorms continued Sunday and
Monday, adding to the misery and leaving 14,000 customers without
electricity in central and northern parts of the state served by
GPU Energy. Some sun was expected Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend forecasters did not impress Julie Lemieux, 38, of
Jefferson Township in Morris County, where a swollen stream behind
her house ran fast and brown, dumping a sandbar in her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't predict anything. Nobody warned us. The weather
forecast said, like, thunderstorms,'' Lemieux said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Jefferson Township were able to begin cleanup efforts
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mlynarz sprayed mud off boat parts in a soggy, muddy back
yard. Several inches of water still stood in the yard along Lake
Hopatcong. On Saturday, rushing waters claimed his dock and garden.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just have a mess to clean up. I don't have any major
damage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those evacuated Monday were 800 children at the Jefferson
Lake day camp in Byram, due to worries about the integrity of a
nearby dam.
</P>
<P>
   A freight line running parallel to Route 517 in Sussex County,
the New York Susquehanna &AMP; Western Railway, was closed at 1 a.m.
Monday because its bed was undermined, State Police spokesman John
Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit trains do not run on that track, but the agency
canceled rush-hour trains between Mount Olive and Hackettstown on
the Boonton and Morristown Line as a precaution in case a dam on
nearby Muscenetcong River burst, spokesman Michael Klufas said.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 commuters affected would be put on buses to Hackettstown
at the Netcong stop, Klufas said. The transit agency also said
there would be no bus or rail service out of Hackettstown Tuesday
morning because of the flooding. A spokeswoman said commuters
should go to the Netcong stop for the train.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing water destroyed the mains in Newton, so residents were
advised to boil water for drinking and cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Route 15, the major link to Sparta, reopened early Monday
morning after crews worked around the clock since Saturday night to
clear tons of silt and mud, and repave a stretch of the highway
north of Interstate 80, state Department of Transportation
spokesman John Dourgarian said. No cost estimate was available.
</P>
<P>
   Three bridges and parts of three roads were swept away in
Sparta, where Main Street residents were evacuated Sunday because
fire officials feared a mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, gawkers flocked to the area to take pictures, where a
road was covered by a swift-running brown river.
</P>
<P>
   The dam on Seneca Lake in Sparta burst over the weekend,
emptying it and leaving a 25-acre patch of mud.
</P>
<P>
   Other dams that have failed include those at Hawthorne Lake in
Sparta, Shawnee Lake in Jefferson, and Lake Tomahawk in Byram,
state officials said. In Stanhope, two sides of the small dam on
Furnace Pond washed away Sunday and the surge broke through the
windows of a nearby paper factory.
</P>
<P>
   Under watch were dams at Saginaw Lake in Ogdensburg, and Sunset
Lake in Sparta, Hagerty said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
