<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Delegates Hear Lawmakers  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Members of Congress are used to speaking to a
nearly empty chamber. On Monday, a parade of lawmakers and
candidates addressing the Democratic National Convention got a
bonus: Some delegates actually listened.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, many of the Democrats in the noisy Staples Center for the
gathering's opening hours were renewing acquaintances, taking
pictures of each other, or simply wandering the aisles. And during
the afternoon many of the seats were empty, which some delegates
blamed on traffic jams outside.
</P>
<P>
   But as Senate candidate Bill Nelson of Florida, Sens. Robert
Torricelli of New Jersey and Barbara Boxer of California, and
others contrasted their party with the Republicans, many others in
the hall were paying rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gives us information we need,'' said Eve Lee, an
attentive delegate from Los Angeles, from beneath a pink baseball
cap to which she had sewn a stuffed elephant. ''And we're getting
energized to carry the message out to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The message the lawmakers delivered seemed designed to fire back
at Republicans, who used their own convention two weeks ago to push
their party toward the political center by casting themselves as
moderate and racially diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ''On every issue that is important to American families, there
is a real and lasting difference'' between Democrats and
Republicans, said Torricelli, who heads his party's Senate campaign
effort.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democrats were the true champions of proposals for
prescription drug benefits, pay equity, and stricter gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, countering GOP charges that the Clinton administration
was one of missed opportunities, cited a litany of accomplishments
including balancing the budget and reducing the crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had our chance, we led, we led,'' Boxer said to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, the convention hall was packed with delegates
anticipating addresses by Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton
and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to that were speeches by the Senate's six women
senators -- Boxer, Dianne Feinstein of California, Blanche Lincoln
of Arkansas, Mary Landrieu of Louisiana, Barbara Mikulski of
Maryland and Patty Murray of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Each focused on Democrats' plans in one area: the environment,
schools, Social Security and Medicare, law enforcement and other
issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
