<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-14 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ervin May Be First Black on US Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Anthony Ervin is virtually assured of
becoming the first black on a U.S. Olympic swim team. He's not
taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin, of Valencia, Calif., was second-fastest in the semifinals
of the 50-meter freestyle Monday night, becoming only the fifth man
to break 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He went 21.92 to finish one-hundredth of a second behind Gary
Hall Jr. The top two in Tuesday's eight-man final earn automatic
Olympic berths.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't expecting it,'' Ervin said. ''I was just hoping and
now that I've done it, I have a lot of confidence going into
finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin, who has a black father and a white mother, all but locked
up his Olympic berth by finishing fifth in the 100 free Sunday
night. The top four are guaranteed spots in the 400 free relay, and
the next two are likely to go, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin said he looks forward to swimming next to Hall in the 50
free final.
</P>
<P>
   ''He lets me know where I am in the race,'' Ervin said. ''It's
always good to have someone who's going to push you in the next
lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other blacks hoping to join Ervin in Sydney didn't make the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Sabir Muhammad of Atlanta was ninth in the 50 free semifinal at
22.75, failing to advance to the final by 0.04 seconds. Muhammad
finished last in the 100 free final.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100 butterfly, Byron Davis of Los Angeles was last among
16 qualifiers in the semifinals at 55.63. Like Muhammad, he had to
finish among the top eight to reach the final.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took solace that Ervin has apparently made the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bound to happen, and I'm glad,'' Davis said. ''Now, we
don't have to talk about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
