<HEADLINE> Campaign Polls Show Diverse Numbers  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The increasing importance of issues over
leadership skills in a new poll of likely voters could be good news
for Democrat Al Gore if the trend holds up.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the likely Democratic nominee have maintained for
months that if the election turns to issues, his strength on topics
like health care, Social Security, the environment and women's
issues like abortion could improve his standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush consistently leads in measures of leadership skills and
personal likability.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll taken Thursday and Friday found that
46 percent thought a candidate's stance on issues is most
important, while 36 percent said leadership skills and vision are
most important.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is important because this is one of the central goals of
the convention, and it's already happening,'' said Democratic
pollster Celinda Lake. She said it's important for Democrats to
shift the focus of the election to issues, rather than personality.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said the Texas
governor ''offers strong leadership and strong positions on the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll results are a reversal from that poll in March, when 50
percent said leadership skills and vision were more important than
a candidate's positions on issues. In fact, leadership skills
scored higher all year until July, when issues and leadership ran
about even.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls have asked for months whether positions on issues or
personal character were more important -- a different question -- and
issue positions consistently scored higher than character. Lake
noted the leadership question is a more potent choice, ''because if
you can't lead, nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Two thirds in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll said Bush has the
personality and leadership skills a president should have, while
half said Gore had those qualities.
</P>
<P>
   While the increased focus on issues could be a plus for Gore,
there was other more troubling news in the poll for the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half, 47 percent, of likely voters said there was no
chance they would vote for Gore, while just 30 percent said that of
Bush. Bush led Gore among likely voters 55 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls have shown Bush with a 10 point lead among
registered voters, including a poll by ICR of Media, Pa., which
showed Bush at 45 percent, Gore at 35 percent, Ralph Nader at 6
percent and Pat Buchanan at 3 percent. The poll of 786 registered
voters taken Wednesday through Sunday had an error margin of 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Some polls have shown the race closer, including an NBC-Wall
Street Journal poll released Sunday showed the race closer, with
Bush at 44 percent and Gore at 41 percent among registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll said they thought
Gore deserves at least a fair amount of credit for the state of the
economy, however. Three-fourths thought his performance in handling
the economy would be about the same as or better than President
Clinton's. More than half, 58 percent, thought he would do a better
job of providing moral leadership for the country.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 641 likely voters was taken Thursday and Friday and
has an error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-14-00 2335 </TRAILER>
