<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Biden: Move Past Indiscretions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- On the day of President Clinton's emotional
convention farewell, Sen. Joseph Biden told Democratic delegates
the party must move past Clinton's ''incredible indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware senator, speaking at a caucus of Iowa delegates,
said of the remainder of the presidential campaign: ''I think we
should make this election about integrity, I think we should make
this election about honesty. Not shy away from it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been so cowered as a party by a guy I love, Bill
Clinton's incredible indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came a few hours before Clinton was to give his
final convention speech as the party's leader in one of the
gathering's emotional high points.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt the very same outrage as every other American felt
about what he did,'' Biden told the Iowa delegates. ''But we should
not because of that back away from anything relating to integrity
and honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden, who has known Clinton for many years, also described a
telephone call he said occurred during the Monica Lewinsky
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''He called me after his first speech relative to the scandal.
Five minutes after, the phone rings. He asks me what I think. I
said, you don't want to know what I think. He said, what do you
mean? I said, you are lucky you are not standing in my library with
me. He said, why? I said, because I'd knock you on your ass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
